"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595631","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>The current membership of the Advisory Committee on Releases to the Environment (ACRE) is:</p><p> </p><p>Professor Rosemary Hails MBE (chair), Centre for Ecology and Hydrology</p><p>Dr Kathy Bamford, Imperial College</p><p>Professor Michael Bonsall, University of Oxford</p><p>Dr Rosemary Collier, University of Warwick</p><p>Professor Ian Crute CBE, self-employed consultant</p><p>Dr Matthew Heard, Centre for Ecology and Hydrology</p><p>Professor David Hopkins, The Royal Agricultural University</p><p>Simon Kerr, National Institute of Agricultural Botany</p><p>Dr Peter Lund, University of Birmingham</p><p>Dr Ben Raymond, University of Exeter</p><p>Dr Andrew Wilcox, Harper Adams University</p><p> </p><p>An updated register of the interests of the Committee members will be published as soon as possible on the ACRE pages of the GOV..UK website. (at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/advisory-committee-on-releases-to-the-environment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/advisory-committee-on-releases-to-the-environment</a>).</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-17T16:32:30.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595631/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595631/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Advisory Committee on Releases to the Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish (a) the revised list of the membership of the Department's Advisory Committee on Releases to the Environment and (b) a revised register of interests of the Committee's members.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","46850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595632","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>Proposals to improve flood defences are made by Defra and its agencies on the basis of the economic benefits, which are assessed in terms of the potential flood damages avoided, the current level of risk and the number homes that would be better protected by the scheme.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-13T11:28:47.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595632/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595632/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45646, on what basis she will make recommendations to HM Treasury on allocation of remaining funding from the £700 million uplift to flood defence and resilience measures.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","46742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595633","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>Local needs are assessed according to the probability of flooding in the area and the damages that could occur as a result of a flood. Investment options are assessed through an appraisal of the benefits and the costs of potential ways of reducing that risk.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-13T11:31:20.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595633/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595633/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45646, how she will assess local needs and value for money to inform decisions on allocating the remaining funding from the £700 million uplift to flood defence and resilience measures.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","46743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595634","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>The assessment of local needs is an ongoing process. The Environment Agency and other risk management authorities are responsible for maintaining up to date assessments of local flood risk. This information, together with an assessment of options to reduce risk in each area, provides an ongoing pipeline of potential works.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-13T11:34:52.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595634/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595634/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45646, when her Department plans to complete the assessment of local needs and value for money to inform decisions on how to allocate remaining funding from the £700 million uplift to flood defence and resilience measures.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","46744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595635","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>The updated and consolidated Control of Trade in Endangered Species (Enforcement) Regulations (COTES) that the Department is taking forward concern the domestic implementation of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species controls. As such we have not discussed the timing of their publication with the European Commission.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the review of COTES legislation Defra has held discussions on guidelines for prosecutors with the Crown Prosecution Service, and sentencing guidelines with the Sentencing Council.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-17T13:27:20.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595635/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595635/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Wildlife: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the European Commission on the timing of the publication of the updated controllers of trade in endangered species regulations on wildlife trade; and what steps her Department is taking to ensure sentencing guidelines for wildlife trade offences are put in place.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","46731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595636","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>The approach Defra takes to monitoring the effectiveness and humaneness of the badger control policy, including the Chief Veterinary Officer’s advice, can be found on GOV.UK.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-17T16:34:14.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595636/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595636/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the (a) humaneness and (b) effectiveness of badger culls since 2013.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","46708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595637","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>In the Woking constituency, the Hoe Valley Flood Alleviation Scheme opened in spring 2012 resulting in better protection to almost 200 properties.</p><p> </p><p>In Surrey, the Environment Agency together with the Lead Local Flood Authorities, are developing a range of flood schemes under the Government’s 6 Year Investment Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The River Thames Scheme for example, will seek to reduce the risk of flooding to 15,000 properties in Surrey and Berkshire. Schemes are also being developed in Guildford, Godalming, Leatherhead and Byfleet.</p><p> </p><p>In the South East the Environment Agency has better protected 42,000 homes between 2010 - 2015 and forecast to better protect nearly 80,000 more homes by 2021.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-13T11:44:33.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595637/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595637/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Flood Control: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she has taken to improve flood defences in (a) Woking constituency, (b) Surrey and (c) the South East since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595638","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>Defra published an updated badger control policy value for money assessment on GOV.UK in August 2016, including estimated costs to government per licensed area.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-17T16:32:54.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595638/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595638/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 3 March 2016 to Question 29007, what recent estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of the badger culls in 2016.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","46818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595639","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>The Government is deeply concerned by the continued poaching of elephants for their ivory, which is why we are committed to maintaining the current global ban on any international trade in new ivory. The UK has made no formal assessment of the impact of other countries’ additional measures to restrict trade in ivory. However, as a further step in delivering the Government’s manifesto commitment to press for a total ban on ivory sales, on 21 September the Secretary of State announced plans for a ban on sales of items containing ivory dated between 1947 and the present day, putting UK rules on ivory sales among the world’s toughest. We will consult on plans for the ban early next year. This will complement the existing UK approach not to permit the trade of raw ivory tusks.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also successfully lobbied for the EU-wide adoption of the existing UK ban on sales of raw ivory tusks, which was advocated through the EU Council Conclusions on an EU Action Plan on Wildlife Trafficking and adopted in June. This urged EU Member States not to issue export or re-export documents under the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) for raw, pre-Convention ivory (pre-1990) and to consider further measures to put a halt to commercial trade in ivory from elephants.</p><p> </p><p>At the CITES Conference that took place from 24 September to 5 October the UK was involved in negotiations that successfully secured a strong agreement calling for the closure of domestic ivory markets where they contribute to poaching or illegal trade. This was agreed by all 183 Parties to CITES.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","46931 ; 47024","2016-10-13T15:34:14.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595639/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595639/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her Department's policy is on seeking a ban on ivory sales.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","47071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595640","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Environment Agency has been working closely with the Official Receiver in order to ensure that the site is being safely overseen by staff under his direction. Whilst staffing matters are for the Official Receiver to decide, the Environment Agency are in regular contact with staff overseeing the former SSI site and do not have any concerns with regards to their environment management.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-12T15:22:00.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595640/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595640/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Sahaviriya Steel Industries UK: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether there are any remaining staff on the former SSI site responsible for environmental management; what estimate she has made of the number of staff responsible for environmental management who are no longer employed; and what assessment she has made of the minimum level of environmental staffing required.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","47133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595641","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-18","<p>The government has a manifesto commitment to introduce a 25 year plan to grow and produce more food, both to increase consumption of British food in the domestic market and to export more.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Food Production to Supply ratio in 2015 was 61% for all food and 76% for indigenous-type food. This compares with 62% and 76% respectively in 2014. This has remained steady over the last decade.</p><p> </p><p>Global food security is dependent on a number of factors including increasing production sustainably, reducing waste and ensuring open markets around the world to facilitate trade.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-18T12:21:17.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595641/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595641/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Self-sufficiency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to address the change in Britain's self-sufficiency rating.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","47111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595642","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-18","<p>There is as yet no single agreed method to estimate the UK's share. The Government is now preparing to negotiate our exit from the EU. Defra is working with the Department for International Trade and the Department for Exiting the EU on the UK’s withdrawal and future trade relationship. As part of this we will have to separate the UK schedules for goods and services at the World Trade Organisation (WTO) from those of the EU. One of the tasks ahead is to examine the UK’s use of tariff rate quotas held by the EU. Defra is in close co-operation with other Government Departments and we will pursue this task in consultation with other WTO Members.</p><p> </p><p>Until we leave the EU current arrangements, including agreements relating to tariff rate quotas, are still in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-18T12:12:58.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595642/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595642/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Agricultural Products: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish an estimate of the UK share of EU tariff rate quotas on agricultural products in (a) each of the last three financial years, (b) 2016-17 and (c) each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","47101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595643","Department of Health","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) Authorised Officers can and do review CCTV footage with the permission of the Food Business Operator (FBO). Where they have grounds to believe an offence has occurred FSA Authorised Officers can seize footage relevant to the offence.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the regular audit and/or inspection process in slaughterhouses an Authorised Officer may ask an FBO for access to CCTV footage. Whilst the outcome of the reviewed footage will be recorded at a local level we do not keep a national log of such requests and therefore the FSA does not hold a record of this information. Similarly, we do not keep a national record of the number of cases where CCTV footage was released.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-17T15:45:43.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595643/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595643/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-07","Slaughterhouses: CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number of requests made to slaughterhouses with CCTV to release their footage for independent review in each of the last five years; and in how many of those cases that footage was released.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","47086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595644","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-14","<p>The National Flood Resilience Review identified that over the next 10 years we could see extreme rainfall events that could be up to 20-30 per cent higher than recent past extreme rainfall events.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency will use 20 and 30 per cent extreme rainfall scenarios with local detailed models used to design new flood risk management schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The scenarios will also be considered for wider flood incident planning and operational readiness that might be needed by relevant responders.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-14T15:10:01.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595644/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595644/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the conclusion in the Flood Resilience Review, published in September 2016, that a 20 to 30 per cent increase in winter rainfall is possible over the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","47112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595645","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>Defra Ministers engage with EU Commissioners on a regular basis, including in the margins of each EU Council meeting. I had an informal discussion with Phil Hogan at the September informal Council. The most recent Ministerial discussions took place at a meeting between Thérèse Coffey and Commissioner Karmenu Vella as part of a conference on CITES.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-17T16:56:08.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595645/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595645/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: European Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which EU commissioners she has met since taking office; and when and where such meetings took place.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595646","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Environment Agency is developing a flood defence scheme for Preston and South Ribble. A full business case is being progressed with detailed modelling and outputs expected during January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to funding and business case approval, the project is expected to improve defences for around 3000 properties and the area from Preston Docks to the M6 at junction 31.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-12T08:18:16.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595646/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595646/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","River Ribble","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to improve flood defences on the River Ribble from the Ribble Estuary to junction 31 of the M6 at Preston; what proposals have been prepared for flood defences along that section of the River Ribble; and what funding is in place to finance such proposals.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","46983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595647","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-13","<p>The Government is deeply concerned by the continued poaching of elephants for their ivory, which is why we are committed to maintaining the current global ban on any international trade in new ivory. The UK has made no formal assessment of the impact of other countries’ additional measures to restrict trade in ivory. However, as a further step in delivering the Government’s manifesto commitment to press for a total ban on ivory sales, on 21 September the Secretary of State announced plans for a ban on sales of items containing ivory dated between 1947 and the present day, putting UK rules on ivory sales among the world’s toughest. We will consult on plans for the ban early next year. This will complement the existing UK approach not to permit the trade of raw ivory tusks.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also successfully lobbied for the EU-wide adoption of the existing UK ban on sales of raw ivory tusks, which was advocated through the EU Council Conclusions on an EU Action Plan on Wildlife Trafficking and adopted in June. This urged EU Member States not to issue export or re-export documents under the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) for raw, pre-Convention ivory (pre-1990) and to consider further measures to put a halt to commercial trade in ivory from elephants.</p><p> </p><p>At the CITES Conference that took place from 24 September to 5 October the UK was involved in negotiations that successfully secured a strong agreement calling for the closure of domestic ivory markets where they contribute to poaching or illegal trade. This was agreed by all 183 Parties to CITES.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","46931 ; 47071","2016-10-13T15:34:14.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595647/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595647/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the impact on the domestic ivory market of plans by other OECD countries to make it illegal to import and export ivory; and if she will make it her policy to impose a total ban on the domestic ivory trade.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595648","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>Livestock associated meticillin resistant <em>Staphylococcus aureus </em>(LA-MRSA) is not a notifiable organism. There is no mandatory requirement to test imports of live breeding pigs or pig meat for the presence of LA-MRSA.</p><p> </p><p>The National Pig Association recommends in its Import Protocol that imported pigs be screened for the presence of MRSA. Such testing is done on a voluntary and private basis.</p><p> </p><p>Any controls or testing introduced for an organism must be proportionate to the risk posed by it. Current advice from the Food Standards Agency (FSA) and Public Health England (PHE) is that LA-MRSA poses a low risk to human health.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-12T15:56:33.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595648/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595648/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Livestock: MRSA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the prevalence of livestock-associated MRSA in live breeder pigs and meat products imported from (a) Denmark and (b) other European countries; what proportion of such imports are voluntarily tested for livestock-associated MRSA; and what analysis her Department has undertaken of the costs and benefits of making it mandatory to test such imports for MRSA.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","47150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595649","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>A UK-wide baseline survey to look for the presence of livestock associated meticillin resistant <em>Staphylococcus aureus</em> (LA-MRSA) in UK pigs was performed in 2008 in line with European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) protocols. At that point, none of the farms tested were found to be positive for MRSA. Since then, the organism has been detected in livestock in the UK. <em>Current advice from the Food Standards Agency (FSA) and Public Health England (PHE) is that LA-MRSA poses a low risk to human health.</em></p><p>The people that are most likely to become colonised by LA-MRSA are those who work with livestock. Defra is therefore undertaking a study with Public Health England (PHE) to investigate the occurrence of LA-MRSA in veterinarians and livestock workers. The results of this study will be used to inform the need for future surveillance.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-12T16:02:11.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595649/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595649/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Pigs: MRSA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to undertake a national monitoring survey of the pig population for the presence of MRSA.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","47151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595650","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>Although government cannot control market volatility, our aim is to give farmers improved tools to manage it. We have extended the period over which they can average their tax from two to five years. We are exploring opportunities for a dairy futures market as well as for better branding and labelling in supermarkets in order to improve profitability. We are also exploring opportunities to help farming businesses become more resilient and ready to take advantage of the growing demand for British dairy products both at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>According to the latest forecast of Farm Business Incomes for 2015-16, average incomes on dairy farms are expected to fall to £46,500. This reflects the impact of lower milk prices which started to fall in March 2014, and the reduced prices for cull cows and heifers. While the number of dairy farms in England and Wales has also fallen from around 13,500 in 2006 to 9,500 today, the number of dairy cows has remained almost unchanged, which suggests consolidation within the industry.</p><p> </p><p>We have seen an increase in the UK farmgate milk price for the second month in a row to 21.34p per litre in August 2016. The long-term picture for our dairy industry remains positive.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","47176","2016-10-17T16:59:53.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595650/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595650/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of falling milk prices on the UK dairy sector.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","47177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595651","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>Although government cannot control market volatility, our aim is to give farmers improved tools to manage it. We have extended the period over which they can average their tax from two to five years. We are exploring opportunities for a dairy futures market as well as for better branding and labelling in supermarkets in order to improve profitability. We are also exploring opportunities to help farming businesses become more resilient and ready to take advantage of the growing demand for British dairy products both at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>According to the latest forecast of Farm Business Incomes for 2015-16, average incomes on dairy farms are expected to fall to £46,500. This reflects the impact of lower milk prices which started to fall in March 2014, and the reduced prices for cull cows and heifers. While the number of dairy farms in England and Wales has also fallen from around 13,500 in 2006 to 9,500 today, the number of dairy cows has remained almost unchanged, which suggests consolidation within the industry.</p><p> </p><p>We have seen an increase in the UK farmgate milk price for the second month in a row to 21.34p per litre in August 2016. The long-term picture for our dairy industry remains positive.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","47177","2016-10-17T16:59:53.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595651/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595651/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to support dairy farmers as a result of reduced milk prices.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","47176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595652","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>Ministers and officials meet with Bayer CropScience, Syngenta and other parties on a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>Information on Ministerial meetings with organisations is available on GOV.UK and is published on a quarterly basis.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-12T16:42:47.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595652/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595652/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials in her Department have had with representatives of (i) Bayer CropScience and (ii) Syngenta in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595653","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government uses the Animal and Plant Health Agency’s National Wildlife Management Centre for advice on trap humaneness.</p><p> </p><p>Of the species currently covered by the Agreement on International Humane Trapping standards (AIHTS), the stoat is the only species regularly and widely trapped in the UK using spring-traps.</p><p> </p><p>When we implement the AIHTS for stoat, the most widely used spring-trap (Fenn type) will no longer be approved for use against stoats. To address this issue, Defra aims to implement the AIHTS as soon as is practically possible, but to use a permitted transition provision to allow delayed implementation of the agreement for stoats whilst a suitable compliant design is identified.</p><p> </p><p>The Fenn type trap is a run-through trap designed to trap animals as they travel through their usual pathways across the landscape.</p><p>The DOC trap meets the required standards but it is only permitted for use as a blind end baited trap. A significant disadvantage of baited traps, such as the DOC, is that stoats will avoid entering baited traps when there is an abundance of preferred food available. These conditions coincide with peak trapping effort to protect game birds and other ground nesting species.</p><p> </p><p>This has led the Government to conclude that the DOC is not a suitable alternative to the Fenn type trap.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-12T15:30:31.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595653/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595653/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-07","Trapping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 44687, on trapping, which animal welfare experts were consulted on trap designs and the decision to delay implementation; and for what reason the DOC trap does not meet the Agreement on International Humane Trapping standards.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","47332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595654","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​On 7 September, during a meeting with Israeli Defence Minister Lieberman in London, I raised our concerns about demolitions. Our Embassy in Tel Aviv also regularly raise our concerns on this issue with the Israeli authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:08:04.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595654/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595654/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Israeli authorities on the demolition of structures inhabited by Palestinians in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595655","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​While we have not made any estimate on the number of EU-funded structures that have been demolished in the West Bank, according to the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) database on demolitions in the West Bank, 271 donor-funded structures have been demolished since the beginning of the year up to 11 June. OCHA measure demolitions of donor-funded structures, we do not know how many of these are EU funded. We have not made any estimates of the costs of reconstruction.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:19:15.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595655/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595655/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate the Government has made of the number of structures in the West Bank funded through EU aid projects that have been demolished by Israeli forces; and what the cost of their reconstruction will be.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595656","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The British Government works closely with the Overseas Territories (OTs) on LGBT rights to ensure that all OTs meet their international human rights obligations in this area.</p><p>In September, the UK Solicitor General chaired a human rights session at the annual conference of OT Attorneys General where LGBT equality was discussed extensively.</p><p>The Solicitor General will co-chair a session in November with the Minister for the Overseas Territories, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, on human rights at the Joint Ministerial Council.</p><p>We expect all Overseas Territory Governments to comply with their evolving international obligations in the field of human rights. Legislating in this area is for OT Governments.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T14:17:30.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595656/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595656/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Falkland Islands: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in the Falkland Islands on improving LGBT rights.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595657","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​We have not had any discussions with the Israeli Committee Against House Demolitions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:09:29.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595657/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595657/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Israeli Committee Against House Demolitions on the demolition of Palestinian homes.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595658","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","The British Government works closely with the Overseas Territories (OTs) on LGBT rights to ensure that all OTs meet their international human rights obligations in this area. In September, the UK Solicitor General chaired a human rights session at the annual conference of OT Attorneys General where LGBT equality was extensively discussed. The Solicitor General will co-chair a session in November with the Minister for the Overseas Territories, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, on human rights at the Joint Ministerial Council. We expect all OT Governments to comply with their evolving international obligations in the field of human rights. Legislating in this area is for OT Governments.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T16:05:23.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595658/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595658/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Turks and Caicos Islands: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in the Turcs and Caicos Islands on improving LGBT rights.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595659","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government laid Montenegro's Protocol of Accession before Parliament on 29 June 2016, under the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010. Following the summer recess, the Protocol completed its Parliamentary scrutiny period on 15 September. We are currently finalising the process to confirm the UK's acceptance of the Protocol and allow us to deposit it with the US Government (depositary for the Treaty), as stipulated by the North Atlantic Treaty. We expect to complete this shortly and look forward to welcoming Montenegro as the 29th NATO Ally, once all current NATO Allies have ratified according to their own national processes.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T15:28:01.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595659/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595659/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Montenegro: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the UK has ratified Montenegro's accession to NATO; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","47202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595660","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","The British Government works closely with the Overseas Territories (OTs) on LGBT rights to ensure that all OTs meet their international human rights obligations in this area. In September, the UK Solicitor General chaired a human rights session at the annual conference of OT Attorneys General, where LGBT equality was extensively discussed. The Solicitor General will co-chair a session in November with the Minister for the Overseas Territories, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, on human rights at the Joint Ministerial Council. And earlier this month, Baroness Anelay addressed LGB&amp;T issues when she spoke to the Cayman Islands Legislative Assembly. We expect all OT Governments to comply with their evolving international obligations in the field of human rights. Legislating in this area is for OT Governments.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T16:10:44.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595660/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595660/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Cayman Islands: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in the Cayman Islands on improving LGBT rights.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595661","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>In order to maximise our ability to persuade all parties to the conflicts in Sudan to end the fighting and allow the Sudanese people the security and development they deserve, we need to have a greater level of direct engagement with the Government of Sudan. The Strategic Dialogue process provides a necessary platform for us to do this, exploring possibilities for cooperation on a wide range of UK interests where our aims align, as well as an avenue to raise concerns.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-12T16:28:49.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595661/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595661/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Sudan: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what outcomes the Government expects from the recent and planned strategic dialogue with the government of Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","47318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595662","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>My officials have been in contact with the UK Border Force about this case. We are aware that the passport presented by Zaina Erhaim has been retained by UK Border Force officials. The passport was listed on an international database as lost or stolen. In such circumstances the Border Force will confiscate the document. Since the passport is listed as lost or stolen, it is no longer valid for travel to the UK or elsewhere and as such the Border Force is not able to return the passport to Ms Erhaim. The passport is therefore being retained by the British authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:54:04.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595662/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595662/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Zaina Erhaim","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the case of the Syrian journalist, Zaina Erhaim.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","47189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595663","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>​The UK Government is opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances. Whenever there is a case of a British national on death row, provided that individual wants assistance from the UK Government, we make political representations at many levels to the government of the country in question. There is no one-size-fits-all approach; we will tailor our interventions on a case-by-case basis in a way that we judge to be most effective to prevent executions being carried out. Beyond political representations by Her Majesty's Government, other interventions might include: engaging local and UK-based Non-Governmental Organisations to provide support to British nationals facing the death penalty; liaising closely with the British national's legal team to ensure any lobbying actions we take complement their ongoing legal activity; and working closely with international partners to encourage wider lobbying.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-12T16:24:56.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595663/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595663/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","British Nationals Abroad: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on preventing the execution of UK nationals sentenced to death abroad.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","47154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595664","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK remains supportive of the Doha Document for Peace in Darfur (DDPD). Through our membership of the Implementation Follow-Up Commission (IFC), we consider regularly what progress has been made on implementation of the DDPD and what further steps need to be taken. The former UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan attended the last meeting of the IFC in May.</p><p>In parallel with this, we continue to urge all parties to the conflict to engage with the African Union-led peace process and reach agreement on the cessation of hostilities and humanitarian access, building on the decisions of both the Government of Sudan and the Opposition to sign the Roadmap peace agreement.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-12T16:32:22.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595664/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595664/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Sudan: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent events in Sudan on the success of the Doha Document for Peace in Darfur.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","47316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595665","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The EU has made absolutely clear that no funding will be provided to the Rapid Support Forces (RSF). We have raised our concerns about the use of the RSF to manage migration directly with the Government of Sudan, most recently during the visit of the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan to Khartoum in September.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-12T16:34:37.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595665/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595665/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the government of Sudan on the use of funds earmarked under the Khartoum Process by Sudan's Rapid Support Forces.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","47317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595666","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The MSc programme was restarted in 2015-16 under the Conflict Security and Stability Fund, reflecting the security focus of the syllabus. It differs from the DFID-funded programme as it draws students from across the region, thereby contributing to the National Security Council (NSC) objective of enhancing regional peace and security in East Africa, whereas the previous MSc was primarily for Ethiopians. There are ongoing efforts to improve the diversity profile of the student intake, in terms of age, gender and military/civilian balance; and to identify more students from African Union countries, in support of the NSC objective to build the African Union's capacity to reduce, manage and resolve conflict and crises in Africa.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:12:34.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595666/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595666/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-07","Ethiopia: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how the current executive MSc in security sector management programme, run in Ethiopia with oversight from his Department, differs from the Department for International Development's similar MSc programme which was closed in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595667","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>There have been no such meetings.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T15:55:01.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595667/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595667/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: European Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which EU commissioners he has met since taking office; and when and where such meetings took place.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595668","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK supported the Governments of France and Spain in their efforts to pass a UN Security Council Resolution on 8th October, calling for an immediate end to the bombardment of Aleppo. This resolution was vetoed by Russia. The UK's Permanent Representative to the United Nations condemned Russia's use of the veto in the strongest possible terms, as &quot;a cynical abuse of the privileges and responsibilities of permanent membership&quot;. We have called repeatedly on Russia at the highest levels to implement a ceasefire in Syria, and to use its influence to deliver this. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) raised his concerns directly with Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov during their meeting on 21 September, and the Prime Minister discussed the situation in Syria with President Putin on 4 September at the G20 Summit. I also refer the Hon. Member to the Foreign Secretary's statement of 11 October (Hansard 11 October 2016, Column 165).</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T16:55:19.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595668/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595668/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations the Government has made to Russia on the breaking of the ceasefire in Aleppo.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595669","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The British Government opposes the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and takes any allegations of extrajudicial killings seriously. The Iranian Government has repeatedly denied that a mass execution took place, though we are aware that between July 1988 and January 1989 executions did take place. However, even with the recording and media reporting on the incident, we have no confirmation of the numbers involved. Although we have no plans to pursue this specific matter we will continue to take action with the international community to press for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including ending the death penalty.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","47084 ; 47085","2016-10-17T16:05:16.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595669/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595669/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Iran: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the people responsible for the massacre of political prisoners in Iran in 1988 are brought to justice.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595670","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Government has been clear in expressing to the Mexican authorities its deep concern over this case.</p><p>The then Prime Minister, the Rt Hon. David Cameron, raised the case with the President of Mexico during his State Visit to the UK in March 2015. The case has also been raised on numerous occasions by other British Ministers, including the then Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) during his visit to Mexico on 2 May.</p><p>We welcome the Mexican Government's agreement to a formal follow-up mechanism with the Inter American Court on Human Rights and urge them to work constructively with the Court to implement the mechanism. Two years on from the disappearance of the students in Ayotzinapa, it is important for the Mexican Government to redouble its efforts to bring the perpetrators to justice.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-18T14:53:45.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595670/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595670/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Mexico: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Mexican government on co-operation with the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights investigation into the disappearance of 43 teacher training students of the Escuela Normal in Ayotzinapa on 26 September 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","47351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595671","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Foreign Secretary discusses Syria regularly with US Secretary of State John Kerry. They last discussed the situation in Syria and the prospects for resuming a political process on 16 October. The UK and US are both working to achieve a full cessation of hostilities, secure country-wide humanitarian access, and implement a strong monitoring mechanism to create the conditions for a resumption of political talks.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:30:52.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595671/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595671/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the Russia-US peace process in Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595672","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​Discussions to re-establish a nationwide Cessation of Hostilities have been led bilaterally between the US and Russia as co-chairs of the International Syria Support Group (ISSG), without wider attendance. The UK participates in full meetings of the ISSG. The Foreign Secretary has attended ISSG meetings accompanied by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's Political Director, the UK's Special Representative for Syria, and Director Middle East and North Africa.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:12:49.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595672/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595672/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which UK officials have been present at discussions on the peace process in Syria between the US and Russia.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595673","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​According to Israeli figures 129 000 British nationals have visited Israel since 1 January 2016, and 50 British nationals have been refused entry into Israel through Ben-Gurion Airport. Of these, 25 sought assistance from the British Embassy. A further 65 British nationals have been refused entry at the Allenby Bridge.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:47:00.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595673/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595673/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens are known to have been (a) detained and (b) delayed when entering Israel in the past 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595674","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​Since January 2016, 25 British nationals who have been detained at Ben-Gurion Airport have requested consular assistance from the UK Embassy.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:47:58.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595674/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595674/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens held in Israel's airport detention facilities have been provided with consular assistance by the UK embassy in Tel Aviv in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595675","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Since January 2016, 15 British nationals have alleged poor treatment by Israeli authorities at border crossings.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T15:59:59.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595675/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595675/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens have raised the issue of poor treatment by Israeli authorities at border crossings and entry points with the (a) UK Government, (b) embassy in Tel Aviv and (c) consulates in Jerusalem and Ramallah in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595676","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Palestinians are not allowed to enter Israel through Ben-Gurion Airport. Dual British/Palestinian nationals enter on their Palestinian documents through Allenby Bridge. We are not aware of any Dual nationals who have been refused entry.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:06:09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595676/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595676/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people with dual Palestinian and British citizenship have been (a) refused entry to, (b) detained by and (c) deported by Israel in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595677","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​We are not aware of any British nationals that have been deported after being allowed entry, with the exception of people who have overstayed their visa.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:05:00.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595677/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595677/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens have been deported by Israel after initially being granted entry to the state in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595678","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​During his visit to Turkey on 25-27 September, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) discussed with Foreign Minister Cavusoglu the situation in South &amp; East Turkey and the outlook for a possible return to a peace process with the PKK. The Foreign Secretary also discussed with several Turkish interlocutors the situation in Northern Syria, where we encourage cooperation amongst all participants within the Global Coalition to focus on combating the threat posed by Daesh.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T16:57:43.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595678/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595678/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Turkey: Kurds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Turkish counterparts during his visit to Turkey between 24 and 27 September 2016 on (a) the rights of Kurdish citizens in Turkey, (b) Kurdish political representation and self-determination within Turkey and (c) Turkish military operations against Kurdish groups in East Turkey and Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595679","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​According to Israeli figures 129 000 British nationals have visited Israel since 1 January 2016, and 50 British nationals have been refused entry into Israel through Ben-Gurion Airport. Of these, 25 sought assistance from the British Embassy. A further 65 British nationals have been refused entry at the Allenby Bridge.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:32:42.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595679/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595679/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Israel: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens are known to have been detained, interrogated and subsequently denied entry by Israel in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","47065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595680","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The British Government opposes the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and takes any allegations of extrajudicial killings seriously. The Iranian Government has repeatedly denied that a mass execution took place, though we are aware that between July 1988 and January 1989 executions did take place. However, even with the recording and media reporting on the incident, we have no confirmation of the numbers involved. Although we have no plans to pursue this specific matter we will continue to take action with the international community to press for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including ending the death penalty.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","47085 ; 47087","2016-10-17T16:05:15.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595680/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595680/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Iran: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he or officials of his Department have had any recent discussions with their Iranian counterparts on the massacre of political prisoners in Iran in 1988.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595681","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The British Government opposes the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and takes any allegations of extrajudicial killings seriously. The Iranian Government has repeatedly denied that a mass execution took place, though we are aware that between July 1988 and January 1989 executions did take place. However, even with the recording and media reporting on the incident, we have no confirmation of the numbers involved. Although we have no plans to pursue this specific matter we will continue to take action with the international community to press for improvements on all human rights issues in Iran, including ending the death penalty.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","47084 ; 47087","2016-10-17T16:05:15.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595681/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595681/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Iran: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the UK Security Council on prosecuting the people responsible for the massacre of political prisoners in Iran in 1988.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595682","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>I am concerned about Mr Ali's case and continue to follow developments. The UK remains firmly opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances. Abolitionist work is high on the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) agenda and is part of the day-to-day work of all diplomatic missions to countries that retain the death penalty. The FCO human rights and democracy report 2015 makes clear our views on the death penalty and the resumption of executions in Pakistan.</p><p>Whilst we have not raised the specific case of Imdad Ali with the Pakistani government, the former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Philip Hammond), raised the issue of the death penalty with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in 2015, and the Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Tobias Ellwood), since wrote to the Pakistani High Commissioner to the UK expressing deep concern about ongoing executions. Together with our EU partners, we continue to raise our concerns about the death penalty with the Government of Pakistan and urge compliance with international obligations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-10-17T15:17:20.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595682/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595682/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Imdad Ali","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Pakistani government on the death penalty imposed on Imdad Ali.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595683","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The International Criminal Court (ICC) has the jurisdiction to judge and prosecute war crimes. However, neither Russia nor Syria are state parties to the Rome Statute, which established the ICC. The only way to secure an investigation by the ICC would be for the UN Security Council (UNSC) to refer the situation in Syria to the ICC. This would require a UNSC resolution. Russia and China vetoed a UNSC resolution which proposed referring all those responsible for war-crimes and crimes against humanity, regardless of affiliation, to the ICC in May 2014. We regularly raise allegations of atrocities being committed in Syria with international counterparts, most recently in the UN Security Council on Saturday 8 October, when Russia vetoed the proposed UNSC resolution calling for an end to the bombardment of Aleppo. Deliberate targeting of civilians or humanitarian personnel would be a war crime. The attack on a UN aid convoy near Aleppo on 19 September was a clear violation of the most basic of humanitarian principles. Russia appears to be partnering with the Syrian regime in the attacks on Aleppo which are causing large numbers of civilian casualties.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:39:50.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595683/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595683/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Russia: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has received evidence that Russia has committed war crimes in Syria; under what international treaties or conventions any such crimes committed by that country fall to be (a) investigated and (b) prosecuted; and what discussions he has had with his European and other counterparts on such crimes.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595684","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The annual Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council (JMC) brings together political leaders from the Overseas Territories and UK Ministers. It will meet this year in London from 1-2 November and will be hosted by the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness Anelay of St Johns DBE.</p><p>An agenda is being developed in partnership with territory leaders and reflects areas key to our shared interests. It is likely to include, but not be limited to, sessions on economic development, good governance and human rights (including child safeguarding), as well as the challenges and opportunities arising from the UK's decision to leave the European Union. A communiqué will be issued following the conclusion of the JMC. The UK Government will update the House by written ministerial statement afterwards.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T14:27:35.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595684/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595684/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the Government expects to host the Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council; what he expects to be on the agenda for that meeting; and what outcomes he expects to achieve from that meeting.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","46808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595685","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Armed conflict with Daesh is non-international in character and is territorially restricted.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:32:23.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595685/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595685/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 August 2016 to Question 43327, whether his Department has classified the international armed conflict with Daesh to be with or without territorial restriction.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","46801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595686","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​It is standard practice to evaluate all Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) programmes and project work. Projects are continuously monitored through regular meetings with stakeholders and implementers, visits and monthly and quarterly reports. The outcome of these evaluations is used to inform and improve any future assistance that we may provide. The FCO provides updates on its programme work in its annual Human Rights report.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:28:49.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595686/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595686/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Bahrain: Technical Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how his Department measures the success of its technical assistant projects in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","46709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595687","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government has not yet concluded that it is right to lift the restrictions on direct UK flights to and from Sharm el-Sheikh. The security of British nationals is the Government's top priority. Our security experts take account of many factors in providing advice on whether it is safe to fly to certain destinations.</p><p>UK aviation security experts have worked closely with their Egyptian counterparts on the ground, sharing their expertise in establishing effective security arrangements. We continue to work in partnership in a spirit of cooperation, and are grateful for Egypt's close engagement and partnership. We look forward to achieving the return of flights once we can be assured that the necessary security environment can be sustained.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:27:20.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595687/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595687/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Egypt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects to be able to advise airlines flying from the UK that it is safe to resume flights to Sharm el-Sheikh, Egypt.","false","Biography information for John Howell","Henley","John Howell","46710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595688","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the violence which has occurred in the Oromia and Amhara regions of Ethiopia throughout 2016 including the high number of deaths.</p><p>We have made clear to the Government of Ethiopia, including at ministerial level, our concerns about the handling of these protests. We have reiterated our strong support for the constitutional right of all Ethiopian citizens to gather peacefully and express their opinions. We also supported the EU's statement of 10 August expressing concern and condolences to those affected, and their statement on the current state of emergency.</p><p>At the Ethiopian state opening on Parliament on Monday 10 October, Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn, announced proposals which Ethiopia hope will address some of the underlying grievances of the wider population.</p><p>We continue to raise our concerns with the Government of Ethiopia both through our bilateral engagement, as well as jointly with our international partners.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T09:21:19.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595688/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595688/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Ethiopia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps his Department has taken to ensure that human rights are being upheld in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","46713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595689","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK's package of technical assistance to support reform in Bahrain began in 2012. Much of it has focused on assisting Bahrain build effective and accountable institutions, assisting the government in ensuring rule of law, police and justice are compliant with international standards and best practice. The specific support that we have provided, and continue to provide, to the Special Investigations Unit has been to assist them to build their capacity to make it more effective in carrying out better investigations and, therefore, build public confidence in the institution itself.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:30:13.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595689/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595689/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Bahrain: Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the UK has provided any specific training to the Special Investigations Unit in Bahrain since it was established in 2013.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","46730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595690","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The US presence on the island of Diego Garcia is governed by a series of agreements, called Exchanges of Notes, of which the overarching agreement sets out the whole Territory should be made available for UK and US defence purposes for an initial 50 year period of 1966 to 2016. If neither side object during a two year window of December 2014 to December 2016, the agreement will continue as it stands until the end of December 2036.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T15:49:01.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595690/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595690/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Diego Garcia: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 44262 on Diego Garcia, since what date the existing procedures referred to have been in place.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","46853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595691","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) has had no direct discussions with his US counterpart on this US-led initiative. He was consulted by Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials, who agreed with their US counterparts the 5 October Joint Declaration for the Export and Subsequent Use of Armed or Strike –Enabled Unmanned Aerial Systems.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-17T14:46:46.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595691/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595691/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","USA: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the Proposed Joint Declaration of Principles for the Export and Subsequent Use of Armed or Strike-Enabled Unmanned Aerial Systems.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","46790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595692","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-17T15:32:59.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595692/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595692/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-07","Brexit: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will publish his Department's negotiating priorities for a  free trade deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595693","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>​As recent progress in Qayyarah in Iraq and Manbij in Syria demonstrates, our strategy of supporting local forces, including with airstrikes is working. The Coalition assesses that Daesh has been driven out of around half the territory it once occupied in Iraq and over 20 per cent in Syria. Thousands of people have been freed from Daesh's rule and many of those who have escaped have now been able to return to their homes. The next major challenges are driving Daesh out of Raqqa and Mosul.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:01:31.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595693/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595693/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress the international coalition is making in its work to defeat Daesh.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","47448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>As Chair of the Ad Hoc Ministerial Committee to Coordinate Support for People Affected by the Terrorist Attacks in Tunisia, I have updated the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), MPs and victims regularly about the Committee's work. There was no commitment to report publicly. The Committee recommended that the lessons it had learned from supporting those affected by the Tunisia attacks benefitted any future victims of terrorism. HMG will ensure that it builds on the work of the Committee in future arrangements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:18:16.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595694/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Tunisia: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the ad hoc Ministerial committee established after the terrorist attacks in Tunisia in 2015 plans to publish its conclusions and recommendations on (a) the support provided by the Government to British nationals or residents affected by those attacks and (b) its recommended support for victims or witnesses of future incidents.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595695","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>In accordance with our international obligations, the UK is required to consider asylum and human rights applications carefully on their individual merits. The Government takes its international responsibilities seriously and will grant protection to those in genuine need.</p><p>Each individual assessment of an asylum claim is made against the background of the latest available country of origin information and any relevant caselaw. The country of origin information is based on evidence taken from a range of reliable sources, including reputable media outlets; local, national and international organisations, including human rights organisations; and information from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p><p>The Home Office’s country of origin information, used in the asylum decision making process, is published on the gov.uk website. It is kept under constant review and updated periodically.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-17T19:27:04.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595695/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595695/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Africa: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which African countries her Department regards as unsafe to return political opposition supporters to.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595696","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK participates in the EU/Africa Khartoum Process; the main regional mechanism for tackling human trafficking and people smuggling in the Horn of Africa most notably from Eritrea.</p><p>We are using our increased engagement with Eritrea to push for the tangible improvements in Eritrea's human rights record, including: amending its national service system; fully implementing its own constitution; and cooperating with international human rights bodies.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T09:24:25.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595696/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595696/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Eritrea: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Eritrea on the increase in political asylum seekers from that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595697","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>Albanians require a visa to travel to the UK and are not allowed to board the plane without one. We do not issue visas for the purpose of claiming asylum in the UK. Unaccompanied children who nonetheless manage to reach the UK, including those from Albania, claim asylum for a variety of reasons. Each case is considered on its individual merits in accordance with our international obligations and protection is granted where it is needed.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-17T18:42:39.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595697/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595697/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Albania: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the reasons for unaccompanied children from Albania seeking to purchase tickets to fly to the UK in order to claim asylum.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595698","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>We were appalled by the murder of Giulio Regeni in Cairo. As soon as we were made aware of reports of Mr Regeni's disappearance on 25 January, we contacted the Italian government to offer our assistance. Foreign and Commonwealth Office Director-General for Middle East and Africa renewed this offer to the Italian Ambassador to London on 22 April. We continue to offer our full support to Italy. I have raised Mr Regeni's case with the Egyptian authorities myself, as have senior officials. In these discussions we have underlined the need for a full and transparent investigation. We remain in contact with both the Italian and Egyptian authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:49:37.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595698/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595698/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Giulio Regeni","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support the Government is giving to Egyptian and Italian authorities investigating the murder of Giulio Regeni.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595699","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK welcomes the release by Joint Incident Assessment Team (JIAT) of the outcome of eight investigations into incidents of alleged breaches of international humanitarian law in Yemen. The Saudi-led Coaltion announced it will immediately investigate the airstrike hitting a funeral hall in the Yemeni capital Sana’a on 8 October along with Joint Incidents Assessment Team (JIAT). I raised my concerns with the Saudi Ambassador to London on 9 October and urged the Saudi-led coalition's announced investigation into the incident to take place as a matter of urgency.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-17T16:57:45.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595699/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595699/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45588, what recent representations he has received from Saudi officials on their Joint Investigation Assessment Team and the timescale for the investigation.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47380"
