"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595904","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-17T18:56:03.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595904/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595904/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Home Office: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of the staff employed by her Department are non-UK nationals.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595905","Home Office","false","2016-10-20","<p>The use of ‘spit hoods’, as with any other use of restraint or force, is an operational matter for Chief Officers. The Home Office is clear that all uses of force or restraint must be necessary and proportionate.</p><p>In recognition of the importance of ensuring transparency in how police forces use various means of restraint, the former Home Secretary asked Chief Constable David Shaw to review what data should be collected and published. The review recommended that forces record a range of data in all instances when significant force is used, including restraint techniques and the use of spit hoods.</p><p>The data to be collected includes the age, gender, ethnicity and sex of the subject, the type of force used, reason for the use of force, and the outcome of the incident.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-20T14:19:32.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595905/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595905/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Police: Spit Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of spit hoods; and what assessment she has made of the extent of use of such hoods by police forces.","false","Biography information for Amanda Solloway","Derby North","Amanda Solloway","47542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595906","Department of Health","false","2016-10-17","<p>The prescribing of injectable opioids, such as methadone or diamorphine (pharmaceutical heroin) as substitutes for illicit heroin, as outlined in the Government’s Modern Crime Prevention Strategy, published in March by the then Home Secretary, has been an option for many years but since the late 1960s, prescribing of diamorphine for the management of addiction has been restricted to licensed addiction specialists.</p><p>The decision to prescribe injectable diamorphine for the treatment of dependence is a clinical matter, for a clinician to take in conjunction with the patient. Advice to guide these decisions is contained in Chapter 5 and Annex 8 of the 2007 UK Guidelines on the Clinical Management of Drug Misuse and Dependence. The guidelines advise that:</p><p>- “injectable opioid treatment may be suitable for a small minority of patients who have failed in optimised oral treatment.”;</p><p>- “clinicians providing injectable opioid treatment should encourage patients not to regard it as a lifelong treatment option and should regularly review their patients and the continuing necessity for this unusual and expensive treatment”; and</p><p>- The use of diamorphine “alone does not constitute drug treatment…it should be seen as on element or pathway within wider packages of planned and integrated drug treatment”.</p><p>The guidelines are currently being reviewed by an Expert Working Group, to take into account developments in the evidence base. In July 2016, the Expert Working Group published their draft update for consultation. The consultation has closed and the responses are being considered by the Expert Working Group.</p><p>Diamorphine is licensed as a medicine by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency. Clinicians wishing to legally prescribe it for the treatment of dependence need to obtain a licence for that purpose from the Home Office and to comply with all other legislation relevant to the safe management, use and supply of medicines which are controlled drugs.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","47471 ; 47473 ; 47629","2016-10-17T15:31:03.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595906/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595906/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-07","Heroin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when and by whom the decision was taken to give heroin to heroin addicts in line with his Department's policy set out on page 31 of Modern Crime Prevention Strategy, published by his predecessor in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595907","Home Office","false","2016-10-20","<p>The Home Office has made no specific assessment of the correlation between people who commit crimes against animals and go on to commit crimes against the person.</p><p>In March this year the Government published the Modern Crime Prevention Strategy. The strategy sets out the evidence that points to six key drivers of crime: drugs; alcohol; the effectiveness of the Criminal Justice System; character (or an individual’s propensity to offend); opportunity; and profit. The strategy can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509831/6.1770_Modern_Crime_Prevention_Strategy_final_WEB_version.pd" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509831/6.1770_Modern_Crime_Prevention_Strategy_final_WEB_version.pd</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-20T14:21:31.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595907/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595907/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Crime: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made an assessment of the correlation between people who commit crimes against animals and go on to commit crimes against the person.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","47519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595908","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>The British people have voted to leave the European Union and the Prime Minister has been clear that their will must be respected and delivered.</p><p>The question of how the UK deals with asylum applicants arriving in the UK from EU Member States and shares information with the EU and international partners will be a key consideration as part of the process of leaving the EU and establishing a new relationship.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-13T14:19:27.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595908/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595908/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to maintain the use of the Dublin System in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595909","Home Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK continues to be a member of the European Union and therefore EU nationals do not require a visa to come to the UK, nor do British citizens require a visa to visit the rest of the EU.</p><p>The Prime Minister has underlined that it would not be right for the Government to give a running commentary on negotiations. It is about developing our own British model so we will not make decisions until we are ready.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-12T12:59:53.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595909/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595909/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","EU Nationals: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to require EU nationals to gain visas before entering the UK in the event of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595910","Home Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>The Assisted Voluntary Returns Service was integrated into the Home Office Voluntary Returns Service (VRS) on 1st January 2016 and provides a range of help and support to those who are here illegally and are seeking to leave the UK voluntarily. The Home Office envisages that the VRS will continue beyond 2020.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-13T14:10:39.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595910/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595910/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Assisted Voluntary Return Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to maintain the Assisted Voluntary Returns schemes after 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595911","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK has received a number of legal challenges regarding alleged delays in accepting asylum seeking children in Calais who assert that they have a legal right to residence in the UK.</p><p>A number of these challenges include cases where the child is yet to seek asylum in France. We are clear that individuals must claim asylum before the UK can consider a transfer request. The recent case of ZAT demonstrates that due process must be followed.</p><p>We are working to improve the operation of the Dublin Regulation and transfer requests are now generally processed within 10 days.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-17T19:46:32.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595911/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595911/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government has received any legal challenge regarding delayed acceptance of child refugees in Calais with a legal right to residence in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595912","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-17T18:54:34.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595912/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595912/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of staff on the payroll of her Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595913","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Home Office does not employ cleaning staff. The cleaning of the Home Office estate is outsourced. The contract requires that all contracted staff have undergone the necessary pre-employment checks and have the right to work in the UK.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-17T18:01:43.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595913/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595913/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of her Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595914","Home Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Home Office has collected disability hate crime data from the police since 2011/12.</p><p>In 2011/12, the police recorded 1,748 disability hate crime offences, 1,911 in 2012/13, 2,006 in 2013/14 and 2,508 in 2014/15.</p><p>Further information on hate crime can be found in Hate Crimes, England and Wales,</p><p>2014/15, available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2014-to-2015</p><p>Data for 2015/16 are due to be published on 13 October 2016 and will be available here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</p><p>As stated by the Office for National Statistics, action taken by police forces to improve their compliance with the National Crime Recording Standard has led to improved recording of crime, especially for violence against the person offences. Together with a greater awareness of disability hate crime, and improved willingness of victims to come forward, this is likely to be a factor in the increase in disability hate crimes recorded by the police.</p><p>This Government is committed to tackling hate crime. The UK has one of the strongest legislative frameworks in the world to tackle hate crime. We are working across Government with police, (including National Community Tensions Team), the Crown Prosecution Service and community partners to send out a clear message that hate crime will not be tolerated and we will vigorously pursue and prosecute those who commit these crimes.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-12T15:48:34.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595914/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595914/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595914/answer/previousversion/13378","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Hate Crime: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many hate crimes were committed against disabled people in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","47598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595915","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-10-18","<p>In 2015 responsibility for construction, maintenance and refurbishment was held by the Parliamentary Estates Department. The Pass Office database shows that 2,529 CTC (Counter Terrorist Check) clearances were conducted on those working in PED in 2015. Of these, 366 were non-UK nationals. This equates to 14.47% of all those given security clearance for work in the department in 2015.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-10-18T16:40:05.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595915/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595915/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-10-07","Palace of Westminster: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what proportion of people given security clearance and passes in 2015 to work for construction, maintenance and refurbishment purposes in the Palace of Westminster were not UK nationals.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595916","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Pass Office database shows that the Palace of Westminster holds security clearance and passes for a total of 779 pass holders whose jobs relate to catering and cleaning purposes. 330 of these are not UK nationals. This equates to 42.36%.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-10-18T16:38:33.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595916/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595916/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-10-07","Palace of Westminster: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what proportion of people who have security clearance for catering and cleaning purposes in the Palace of Westminster are not UK nationals.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595917","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:10:40.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595917/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595917/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Department for International Development: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of the staff employed by her Department are non-UK nationals.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595918","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>Since January 2015 there have been no instances where DFID Procurement and Commercial Department (PCD) have excluded a company from a Public Procurement for the circumstances cited.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-12T16:25:02.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595918/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595918/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Department for International Development: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many companies her Department has excluded from public procurement for (a) a conviction for wrongdoing defined by the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 or (b) grave professional misconduct since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","47275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595919","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Secretary of State has been monitoring the impact of Hurricane Matthew closely and has announced up to £5 million to support Haiti where many of those most affected live. The DFID team in Haiti and Foreign and Commonwealth Office embassies and High Commissions in the region are in close contact with relevant authorities in order to understand the impact and programme these funds effectively.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:06:33.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595919/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595919/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what representations she has made to her counterparts in (a) Haiti, (b) Jamaica, (c) Cuba and (d) the Bahamas on humanitarian aid to address the damage caused by hurricane Matthew.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595920","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Department for International Development has helped humanitarian organisations, including Médécins Sans Frontières, engage with the Government of Saudi Arabia on the humanitarian crisis in Yemen. However, we do not fund MSF’s activities inside Yemen. We do fund medical assistance in Yemen through UNICEF and the United Nations Humanitarian Pooled Fund.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:09:20.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595920/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595920/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Yemen: Medecins Sans Frontieres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to assist Medicins Sans Frontieres in offering medical assistance in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","47360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595921","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>In Haiti, the Department is working with the United Nations, international partners and the Government of Haiti to assess the level of humanitarian need. The Government of Haiti and the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs estimate 2.1 million people in Haiti have been affected by Hurricane Matthew. We are now beginning to see the full scale of the devastation wrought by the worst storm to hit this region in almost a decade.</p><p>In Jamaica, no significant humanitarian need has been identified. In respect of Cuba, the Department is working closely with the International Federation of the Red Cross to ascertain their understanding of needs and potential response plans. We are also working with the British Red Cross to deepen our understanding of the humanitarian situation in the Bahamas.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:02:05.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595921/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595921/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in (a) Haiti, (b) Jamaica, (c) Cuba and (d) the Bahamas as a result of hurricane Matthew.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595922","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK is committing up to £5 million of initial support to trusted UN, Red Cross and NGO partners to help thousands of people in Haiti affected by Hurricane Matthew. DFID prepositioned aid in Haiti to better prepare the country for natural disasters, and has a team in Haiti working with international partners and the Government of Haiti to address the humanitarian situation.</p><p>In Jamaica, no significant humanitarian need has been identified. In respect of Cuba, the Department is working closely with the International Federation of the Red Cross to ascertain their understanding of needs and potential response plans.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence and Foreign and Commonwealth Office deployed the British Royal Fleet Auxiliary Vessel Wave Knight to the Bahamas to provide aerial reconnaissance and support in the immediate aftermath of Matthew’s impact. The Department for International Development is working with the British Red Cross to deepen our understanding of the humanitarian situation in the Bahamas.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:05:00.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595922/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595922/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Caribbean: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to address the humanitarian situation in (a) Haiti, (b) Jamaica, (c) Cuba and (d) the Bahamas caused by hurricane Matthew.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595923","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Fifth Replenishment Conference for the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria took place on 15 and 16 September in Montreal, Canada.</p><p>At the conference, the Secretary of State announced an investment of £1.1billion in the Global Fund, including a commitment to double private sector contributions for tackling malaria, up to a maximum of £200million, and £90million linked to successful delivery against a performance agreement.</p><p>The UK’s investment will help to fund 40million bednets to tackle malaria; provide enough lifesaving anti-retroviral therapy for 1.3million people with HIV; and support the treatment of 800,000 people with tuberculosis. Overall, our investment will help the Global Fund to save 8million lives, avert 300million infections and help build resilient and sustainable systems for health.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-12T14:06:00.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595923/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595923/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Overseas Aid: Infectious Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding the Government has committed to the Global Fund Investment Case, Fifth Replenishment 2017-19 for fighting infections.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","47346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595924","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK regularly raises the issue of water in the Occupied Palestinian Territories with the Israeli authorities, most recently on 8 September. We continue to stress the urgent need for Israel to take immediate and practical measures to improve the current situation and ensure fair distribution of water in the West Bank and Gaza.</p><p>We encourage both parties to find a swift resolution to this issue and to reconvene the Joint Water Committee to facilitate approval of projects that will improve Palestinian access to water. We see continuity of supply to the West Bank as essential for both the basic needs of Palestinians and for stability and security more widely.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:07:47.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595924/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595924/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","West Bank: Water Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent representations she has made to the Israeli authorities on the effect on the Palestinians in the West Bank of restricting water supplies.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595925","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>DFID utilises a cross government contract for cleaning services in their UK estates.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:11:18.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595925/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595925/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of her Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595926","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:11:58.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595926/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595926/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of staff on the payroll of her Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595927","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK assesses that the Palestinian Authority (PA) is not in breach of its commitment to respecting human rights. The UK promptly raises specific human rights issues with the PA when necessary, both publicly and privately.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:12:54.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595927/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595927/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to section 6.5 of the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian National Authority, whether her Department has been aware of any breach of the commitment of human rights and taken any action in response to a breach of that commitment.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595928","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK deplores incitement on both sides of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. We take the issue very seriously and raise our concerns when incidents occur. The UK’s assessment is that the Palestinian Authority is not in breach of the Memorandum of Understanding and the track record of President Abbas and Prime Minister Hamdallah demonstrates their overall commitment to non-violence and a negotiated two-state solution.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:13:44.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595928/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595928/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to section 6.5 of the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian National Authority, whether her Department has been aware of any breach of the commitment on the principle of non-violence and taken any action in response to a breach of that commitment.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595929","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK raised the issue of human rights as part of the FCO-led UK-Palestinian strategic talks and in the DFID- Palestinian Authority (PA) annual talks that review the broader DFID-PA Memorandum of Understanding (MoU), with a clear message that we take very seriously any allegations of human rights abuses. The UK assesses that the PA is not in breach of its commitment to respecting human rights.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:14:29.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595929/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595929/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to section 6.5 of the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian National Authority, whether the implications of any breach of the commitment on human rights was discussed at the annual partnership talks between her Department and that Authority.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595930","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK raised the issue of incitement as part of the FCO-led UK-Palestinian strategic talks and in the DFID-Palestinian Authority (PA) annual talks that review the DFID-PA Memorandum of Understanding (MoU), sending a clear message of discouraging incitement to violence. The UK’s assessment is that the PA is not in breach of the MoU and the track record of President Abbas and Prime Minister Hamdallah demonstrates their overall commitment to non-violence and a negotiated two-state solution.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:15:28.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595930/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595930/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to section 6.5 of the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Palestinian National Authority, whether the implications of any breach of the commitment on the principle of non-violence was discussed at the annual partnership talks between her Department and that Authority.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595931","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The list of vetted civil servants is held by the European Union. DFID has access to this list on request. The list of eligible beneficiaries is subject to a vetting process that includes screening against international and ad hoc sanctions lists, covering a large number of different risk categories including terrorism financing.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:16:10.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595931/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595931/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with regard to the amendment letter to the Memorandum of Understanding with the Palestinian Government for Financial Assistance, signed on 19 March 2015, whether her Department has a list of the eligible beneficiaries of the PEGASE support programme; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","47607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595932","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>DFID does not routinely publish Partnership Principles assessments. These assessments are used to inform the annual dialogue between DFID and the Palestinian Authority (PA). Our assessment is that the PA continues to deliver on the Partnership Principles.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-12T16:19:58.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595932/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595932/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 19 September 2016 to Question 45930, on the Palestinian Authority, if she will place a copy of her Department's formal assessment of the Palestinian Authority's commitment to the Partnership Principles in the Library.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","46979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595933","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>In 2011 DFID approved an allocation of £285.5 million for the airport at St Helena.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:54:48.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595933/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595933/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","St Helena: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the cost to the public purse is of the airport at St Helena.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595934","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>DFID is working with our partners to ensure that sexual and reproductive health needs of girls and women affected by crises are prioritised. This includes their right to experience menstruation with dignity. In 2015 alone, UK funding to UNFPA supported their efforts to distribute almost 60,000 menstrual hygiene kits to women and girls living in conflict situations. The UK has committed that, in humanitarian crises, DFID calls for proposals will require the sexual and reproductive health and rights of women and girls to be considered. The UK also supported a joint statement led by UNFPA, highlighting the importance of sexual and reproductive rights in crises, at the World Humanitarian Summit in May this year.</p><p>DFID is working globally with a network of civil-society organisations, private sector companies, donors, academics, and international agencies to address stigma and increase access for all women and girls to the education, support, products and services they need to manage menstruation with dignity.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-14T12:11:55.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595934/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595934/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Refugees: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with (a) her international counterparts, (b) non-governmental organisations and (c) toiletry companies on the provision of women's health and sanitary products to refugee women and girls.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595935","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK, as a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) Development Assistance Committee (DAC), is committed to transparent reporting of development assistance in a way that permits international comparisons. Whilst comparison codes are available to separately identify funding for family planning and for reproductive, maternal, newborn and child health, the same is not true specifically for women's health initiatives.</p><p>DFID is in the process of developing our plans to 2020, so future spending has not yet been determined.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-14T11:14:39.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595935/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595935/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the Department's funding has been allocated to women's health initiatives, including education in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18 and (c) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595936","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>My Department will continue to fund innovative projects on anti-corruption and transparency. The Secretary of State for International Development has confirmed that transparency and accountability are at the top of her agenda. Moreover the London Anti-Corruption Summit committed to a range of innovative approaches to fighting corruption globally, many of which DFID will support. This includes increased use of company beneficial ownership registers and improved open public contracting standards. DFID will also contribute towards a new UK-led Anti-Corruption Innovation Hub. It will establish a network across countries, businesses and civil society to share know-how, identify opportunities for collaboration and connect technology and data experts with law enforcement and civil society.</p><p>DFID has refreshed anti-corruption strategies for our priority country programmes. These take into account the issues and ambitions created by the Summit and the forthcoming UK Anti-Corruption Strategy. DFID will support our partner countries to implement their Summit commitments where appropriate.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:45:57.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595936/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595936/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department plans to continue to fund (a) innovative projects on anti-corruption and transparency and (b) country-specific anti-corruption strategies.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","46778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595937","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>We require our centrally funded civil society and private sector suppliers to publish details of how they spend UK funding in line with international transparency standards. The department has also reviewed the extent to which multilateral partners are meeting or going beyond these standards, to promote transparency globally and in the countries where they work. DFID supported adoption of new international commitments relating to transparency and anti-corruption, including commitments in the “Grand Bargain” for humanitarian action, and under Cabinet Office leadership, the Open Government Partnership. DFID has increased, and continues to increase, country programming on tax and other areas supporting fiscal transparency.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:50:08.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595937/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595937/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she has taken to ensure that every government and organisation which her Department funds meets global transparency standards.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","46779"
