"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595943","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-13","<p>The UK Government is playing a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries. DFID has a range of programmes which are working with developing countries to ensure renewable energy markets work effectively as well as supporting energy businesses to grow, and providing consumers with access to funding to buy solar goods. For example, our Energy Access Ventures programme is investing in off-grid electric and we are delivering green mini-grid solutions across Africa.</p><p>Through the UK Government’s Energy Africa campaign we are working with solar firms to help them access the finance they need to expand their businesses, create jobs and help reach millions of people in Africa without electricity access.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-13T16:29:36.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595943/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595943/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department has taken to increase investment in decentralised renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","47022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595944","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>On 21 September, the UK announced an extra £40 million of humanitarian funding to Iraq, on top of £50 million committed earlier this year. This brings our total commitment in Iraq to £169.5 million since June 2014. This support will provide emergency life-saving assistance – such as food, shelter, medical and protection services – to support the Government of Iraq-led Mosul humanitarian response as well as continuing to provide assistance for displaced and vulnerable people across the country.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-12T16:22:02.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595944/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595944/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Iraq: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government has made plans to assist with additional funding or aid subsequent to the changes in refugee numbers entering into Mosul.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","47028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595945","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>During her attendance at the Foreign Affairs Council- Development on the 12<sup>th</sup> September 2016 the Secretary of State met with the European Commissioner for International Cooperation and Development, Neven Mimica, and the Vice President of the European Commission and High Representative of the European Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy, Federica Mogherini.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:56:19.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595945/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595945/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Department for International Development: European Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which EU commissioners she has met since taking office; and when and where such meetings took place.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595946","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>UK non-Overseas Development Assistance support for the Executive Masters Programme in Security Sector Management – totalling £140,000 - covered the costs of the non-civilian students that attended the course.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-14T10:54:16.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595946/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595946/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Ethiopia: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45678, on Ethiopia: security, what non-overseas development assistance elements were included in the executive masters programme in security sector management, which closed in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595947","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>DFID uses a range of criteria to determine allocations to countries, including the need of those countries for development assistance, how effective our assistance is likely to be in those countries, and the strategic fit with UK government priorities.</p><p>The 50% commitment is not only the right thing to do but also the smart thing to do for Britain’s national interest. The commitment ensures that we improve the lives of the poorest and most vulnerable people in the world. Poverty is increasingly concentrated in fragile states and regions, and conflict is one of the major challenges to development. Over half of the world’s poor live in fragile states.</p><p>Our work in fragile states and regions will help to build stability, prevent conflict and support economic growth in the world’s poorest countries and regions. Without stability, our gains on poverty reduction risk being reversed.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-12T16:24:34.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595947/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595947/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made an assessment of the effect of changing levels of funding for non-conflicting affected states on the level of stability in those countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","47243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595948","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>DFID’s expenditure on HIV and AIDS is now overwhelmingly directed through our multilateral support: our £1.1billion investment in the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria for the period 2017-19 and our work with UNITAID and UNAIDS.</p><p>Strategic investments in DFID country programmes support this. Direct bilateral budget expenditure specifically coded under HIV prevention, treatment and care amounts to £18.3million for 2016/17 according to the UK AID Development Tracker; which can be found on our website at <a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/sector/2/categories/130/projects/13040" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/sector/2/categories/130/projects/13040</a>.</p><p>This supports regional programmes and projects in 8 DFID countries. This coding itself captures only part of our bilateral work: a range of investments not coded under HIV will also support the AIDS response, especially in the highest prevalence countries.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-12T14:02:50.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595948/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595948/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many of her Department's country offices have direct bilateral expenditure that is coded under HIV prevention, treatment and care; and what the value of that expenditure is.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","47335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595949","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK remains extremely concerned about continued Israeli settlement expansion and the large increase in demolitions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories since the start of 2016, compared to the monthly average in 2015. We continue to raise these issues with the Israeli authorities. Demolitions and the evictions of Palestinians from their homes cause unnecessary suffering, are harmful to the peace process, and in all but the most exceptional of cases are contrary to international humanitarian law.</p><p>The UK supports Palestinians facing demolition or eviction and displacement by funding a legal aid programme to help individuals and communities challenge these decisions in the Israeli legal system.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:58:40.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595949/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595949/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is giving to Palestinians displaced by Israeli settlement building and the demolition of Palestinian homes.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595950","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK government is committed to ensuring access to low cost, effective medicines in the developing world. We support the provision of essential medicines and other health products through global partnerships such as the Global Fund for AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM), UNITAID, Gavi the Vaccine Alliance, and the Medicines Patent Pool (MPP). We place a great emphasis on research and development of new vaccines, medicines and diagnostics for conditions that affect millions of poor people. For example, the UK is a leading investor in public-private Product Development Partnerships (PDPs), an innovative financing mechanism to stimulate research and development (R&amp;D) where market incentives are insufficient.</p><p>We support the aims of the UN High Level Panel on Access to Medicines and welcome efforts to shed light on this important issue. However, we note that this panel of experts could not reach agreement on the best approach, given the evidence presented. Our view is that the World Health Organisation (WHO) has already undertaken a large amount of work to consider the full range of barriers that limit access to medicines, and is well placed to consider which recommendations add the most value.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-12T14:05:03.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595950/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595950/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the recommendations in the UN High Level Panel on Access to Medicines report, published in September 2016, on stimulating research and development in underfunded areas and improving access to medicines; whether she has plans to take those recommendations forward; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","47336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595951","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK is recognised as a global leader in tax and development, working to end aid dependency in developing countries. The UK, as a founding signatory to the Addis Tax Initiative, pledged to double our spend on tax and development by 2020. My Department has made strong progress and is on course to deliver this commitment by 2020.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T17:00:48.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595951/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595951/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Developing Countries: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to page 21 of her Department's Annual Report and Accounts 2015-16, what assessment she has made of progress against its target of doubling its funding on improving tax systems in developing countries by 2020.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","47230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595952","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-14","<p>No structures that the UK has funded bilaterally in the West Bank have been demolished. A number of structures funded by the EU’s Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection Office (ECHO) have been demolished in recent months.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-14T16:59:12.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595952/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595952/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-07","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many of the structures in the West Bank funded through aid provided by her Department have been demolished by Israeli forces in 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","47227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595953","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Ministers have outlined their programme of work to improve the courts in the ‘Transforming our Justice System’ document and consultation published on 15 September. As part of this work we will be considering how we can improve the civil enforcement process.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T16:57:24.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595953/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595953/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Companies: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has to allow commercial companies access to sensitive information held by other government departments and agencies on the proposed enforcement purposes of those companies.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595954","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-18","<p>Well-run prisons are fundamental to the proper functioning of our justice system, and a vital part of our reform plans. Private providers play an important role in the prison estate. Performance of all providers is closely monitored and we will not hesitate to take action where standards fall short.</p><p>Prison Contracts set out a strict performance framework, consisting of prescriptive performance targets. Failure by the provider to meet performance targets results in performance points being applied.</p><p>Performance points are awarded according to the severity of failure. If the total number of points exceeds the agreed baseline for the performance quarter or year, financial remedies are applied against the Contractor in accordance with the Contract. In certain circumstances financial remedies can also be applied directly, without performance points being accrued. The amount of points awarded therefore cannot always be linked to the value of remedies imposed.</p><p>The number of performance points incurred at HMP Birmingham and HMP Oakwood for the reporting years 2012-2013 through to 2015-2016 are as follows.</p><p>Data for reporting year 2016-2017 is not yet available as it has not been finalised.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Points</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Points</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Points</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Points</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><strong>Birmingham</strong></p></td><td><p><em>Failure to comply with procedures</em></p></td><td><p><em>0</em></p></td><td><p>248.9</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Incidents</em></p></td><td><p><em>0</em></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Failure to comply with prison regime</em></p></td><td><p><em>135</em></p></td><td><p>45.71</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><strong>Oakwood</strong></p></td><td><p><em>Failure to comply with procedures</em></p></td><td><p><em>7</em></p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Incidents</em></p></td><td><p><em>0</em></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Failure to comply with prison regime</em></p></td><td><p><em>90</em></p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-18T09:35:20.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595954/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595954/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Birmingham Prison and Oakwood Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the contractual agreement between her Department and G4S Care and Justice Services (UK) Limited at HM Prison (a) Birmingham and (b) Oakwood, how many performance points have been incurred and for what reason those performance points have been incurred in each year from 2012-13 to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","47220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595955","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>HMCTS are considering a range of options about how best to deliver this service. The tender process will allow HMCTS to make informed decisions about what is in the best interests of the service and the taxpayer. No decision on the way forward for the Civilian Enforcement Office role has been made at the current time.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:36:32.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595955/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595955/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason her Department has invited private sector companies to tender for work currently carried out by its civilian enforcement officers.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595956","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Civil Service Code only applies to Civil Servants. There is however a contractual expectation that privately contracted services are carried out in line with Ministry of Justice principles and policy.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T16:55:15.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595956/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595956/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Civil Servants: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason the Civil Service Code does not apply to those undertaking public sector work for her Department in the private sector.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595957","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-12","<p>Privately Managed prison contracts contain provisions which allow financial remedies to be applied for non-performance.</p><p> </p><p>Performance points are awarded according to the severity of failure. If the total number of points exceeds the agreed baseline for the performance quarter or year, financial remedies are applied against the Contractor in accordance with the Contract.</p><p> </p><p>As financial remedies are only applied if baseline targets are exceeded it is not, possible to link individual incidents to the value of remedies that have been applied due to this cumulative effect.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-12T16:45:07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595957/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595957/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Birmingham Prison and Oakwood Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the contractual agreement between her Department and G4S Care and Justice Services (UK) Limited at HM Prison (a) Birmingham and (b) Oakwood for what reason financial remedies have been levied in (i) failure to comply with procedures, (ii) incidents and (iii) failure to comply with prison regime in each year from 2012-13 to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","47319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595958","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-13","<p>Between January 2016 and March 2016 (the latest date for which figures are available), 715 offenders were recalled to prison whilst residing in an approved premises.</p><p> </p><p>We are unable to give an accurate figure for the proportion of departures from an approved premises that were attributable to the offender being recalled to custody. This is because some residents of an approved premises are not offenders released from custody on licence; in terms of departures, these cannot be distinguished from other residents.</p><p> </p><p>Approved premises provide for effective supervision of certain high risk of harm offenders, particularly on release from custody. It would not be possible to provide such effective supervision elsewhere in the community, which is the only alternative for offenders who have completed the custodial part of their sentence. Offenders who breach their licence conditions (including the rules of residence of an approved premises in which they are required to reside) are liable to be recalled to custody, in order to protect the public.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-13T16:45:41.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595958/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595958/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of prisoners released on licence to a bail hostel have been subsequently recalled to prison in 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","47323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595959","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","The First-tier Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum Chamber) is administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS). HMCTS have provided an additional 4,500 tribunal sitting days for this financial year compared to 2015/16. HMCTS keeps performance and resource levels under close review.","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T12:46:22.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595959/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595959/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Asylum: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to increase capacity at the Asylum and Immigration Chamber.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","47206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595960","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The accelerated procedure for obtaining a possession order to evict trespassers (which may include travellers) is set out in the Civil Procedure Rules, Part 55.</p><p> </p><p>There is no notice period once a landowner has obtained an order to evict. The standard order for a successful claim for possession would be an order for immediate possession.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not consider that the process requires change.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","47245","2016-10-17T13:19:04.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595960/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595960/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make an assessment of potential measures to make access to courts (a) easier and (b) substantially faster for a landowner seeking to get an order to evict travellers.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","47244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595961","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-12","<p>Section 363 of the Communications Act 2003 provides that a person who installs or uses a television receiver without being authorised by a licence is guilty of a criminal offence. As of 1 September 2016, this includes watching BBC on-demand services such as the iPlayer.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-12T09:24:12.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595961/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595961/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-07","BBC: Video on Demand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether non-payment of the television licence for solely accessing the BBC iPlayer will be treated as a criminal or civil offence.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","46995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595962","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:33:10.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595962/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595962/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in what proportion of child contact cases presided over by the family judiciary in each year since 2010, where there was an allegation of domestic abuse, either party were litigants in person.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","47052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595963","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>We do not hold statistics on the number of offenders found guilty under Section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015, as the offence has yet to be commenced.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T13:01:56.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595963/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595963/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information her Department holds on how many times provisions under Section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 have been used to convict people in (a) Northern Ireland and (b) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595964","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-12","<p>Information on the employment status of prisoners beyond the point of release is not available centrally and can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>All other information requested can be found on GOV.UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-12T16:47:22.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595964/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595964/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of people released from each prison in England and Wales (i) reoffended and (ii) went into employment within six months of their release in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","46986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595965","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-18","<p>Safety in prisons is fundamental to the proper functioning of our justice system and a vital part of our reform plans. We do not tolerate violence or bullying in prisons and take appropriate action against victimisation of any kind.</p><p> </p><p>Gang membership and youth violence cause serious harm to those involved and their communities. The Government is committed to reducing the likelihood of young people joining gangs, and to responding effectively when they do.</p><p> </p><p>Many young and vulnerable people come into contact with the criminal justice system as a result of their involvement with gangs.</p><p> </p><p>Prison gives young people the opportunity to leave gangs behind and lead safe and productive lives in their communities. Prison staff work with the police to tackle gang related activity in prison, and to provide new opportunities for young people.</p><p>All offenders entering prison participate in induction programmes designed to help them make the most from their time in that prison. Some prisons have appointed a gangs officer, and prison staff work closely with the police to respond where gang members are coming into prison.</p><p> </p><p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) will shortly issue guidance to all prison staff to help them identify gang members, take action against gang related violence and help them use their time in prison to leave gangs behind. The Identity Matters programme is specifically designed to help prisoners disengage from gangs and stop offending.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-18T09:37:54.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595965/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595965/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","First Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department has taken to ensure first-time offenders entering the prison system are (a) made aware of gang culture in prisons and (b) discouraged from becoming involved in that culture.","false","Biography information for Amanda Solloway","Derby North","Amanda Solloway","47120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595966","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Victims of specific sexual offences, including historical sex abuse cases, are automatically provided with lifetime anonymity, by way of reporting restrictions, from the point of complaint. Anonymity is granted in recognition of the nature of the offence against them and to encourage other victims to come forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T15:53:59.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595966/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595966/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Offences against Children: Victims and Witnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what safeguards are in place to protect the privacy of victims and witnesses in historic sex abuse cases.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","47059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595967","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The number of arrest warrants issued for defendants who failed to attend court in England and Wales for the period 2010 to 2014, the latest data available, can be viewed in the table below.</p><p><strong>Number of Failure to Appear (FTA) Warrants received<sup> (1)</sup> in England and Wales, 2010- 2014.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total warrants issued</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>93,473</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>88,788</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012<sup> (2)</sup></p></td><td><p>72,819</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>70,225</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014<sup> (3)</sup></p></td><td><p>70,016</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(1) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from live systems used by police forces principally for operational reasons. As such, they are subject to change over time. For these reasons, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(2) West Midlands constabulary are unable to supply any FTA warrant data from 1 April 2012.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(3) Lincolnshire Police were unable to supply any data for Q4 of 2014 because of technical issues related to the introduction of a new warrant management system. Data presented are for the first three quarters of 2014 only.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Notes:</strong><ul><li>These data are reported to the Ministry of Justice by police forces. As such, they are not directly comparable with other data presented in the Criminal Statistics bulletin, which are returned directly from administrative data systems used by magistrates' courts and the Crown Court.</li></ul></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T15:38:47.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595967/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595967/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many arrest warrants were issued for defendants who failed to attend court in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595968","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Modern Slavery Act 2015 increased the maximum sentence for modern slavery offences from 14 years to life imprisonment. The Act also gave law enforcement agencies the power to seize traffickers’ assets and introduced risk and prevention orders which restrict the activities of traffickers outside prison if they are judged to pose a serious threat.</p><p>Earlier this year, the Government commissioned the barrister Caroline Haughey to carry out an independent review of the operation of the criminal justice provisions in the Modern Slavery Act. Ms Haughey found that the Act had set an international benchmark to which other jurisdictions aspire, and recommended that we do more to ensure that law enforcement agencies use the Act to full effect.</p><p>The Government agrees and the Prime Minister recently announced that she will be chairing a modern slavery taskforce to ensure that we leave no stone unturned in bringing the perpetrators of this vile crime to justice.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-17T16:48:55.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595968/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595968/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to make the punishment of people traffickers more severe to increase its deterrent effect.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","47074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595969","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The number of male offenders aged over 10 and under 21 sentenced to immediate custody, and the custody rate for indictable offences, at all courts in Wales, by police service area, from 2010 to 2015, is provided in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Male offenders aged under 21 sentenced at all courts to immediate custody for all offences, and custody rate for indictable offences, by police area, Wales, 2010 to 2015 <sup>(1)(2) </sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Police Area</p></td><td><p>Immediate custody</p></td><td><p>Custody rate for Indictable offences <sup>(3)</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>251</p></td><td><p>65%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>176</p></td><td><p>64%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>567</p></td><td><p>72%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>67</p></td><td><p>58%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>188</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>151</p></td><td><p>60%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>480</p></td><td><p>72%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>67</p></td><td><p>67%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>166</p></td><td><p>83%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>73%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>343</p></td><td><p>68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>63%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>63%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>126</p></td><td><p>83%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>312</p></td><td><p>66%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>41</p></td><td><p>89%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>104</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>133</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>315</p></td><td><p>66%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>57</p></td><td><p>56%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>North Wales</p></td><td><p>107</p></td><td><p>59%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Gwent</p></td><td><p>104</p></td><td><p>50%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>South Wales</p></td><td><p>280</p></td><td><p>59%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Dyfed Powys</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>40%</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td rowspan="6"><p>Total Wales</p></td><td><p>1,061</p></td><td><p>68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>886</p></td><td><p>70%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>724</p></td><td><p>73%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p>69%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>609</p></td><td><p>65%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>538</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(1) The sentence shown is the most severe sentence given for the principal offence (i.e. the principal sentence), secondary sentences given for the principal offence and sentences for non-principal offences are not counted in the tables.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(3) The proportion of offenders sentenced for indictable offences who are sentenced to immediate custody.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Statistics for 2016 are not currently available, but will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:42:43.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595969/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595969/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prison Sentences: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many male offenders aged under 21 were sentenced to immediate custody in courts in each police force area in Wales in each year from 2010 to 2016; and what the custody rate for indictable offences was during that period.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595970","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Data on Failure to Appear (FTA) warrants collected by the Ministry of Justice includes information on the category of warrant but does not include information on the specific offence for which the defendant is being sought. This information has been provided in response to Parliamentary Question 47082.</p><p>It would not be possible to separately identify those defendants for whom a warrant was issued in connection with failing to appear in court for a sexual offence without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-17T12:33:17.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595970/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595970/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Arrest Warrants: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many arrest warrants have been issued for people sentenced for a serious sexual offence who failed to appear in court for sentencing in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595971","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-14","<p>Information on whether or not a defendant is in attendance at their hearing is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","47079","2016-10-14T12:22:43.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595971/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595971/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were prosecuted in their absence for (a) serious sexual offences, (b) class A drug use and (c) manslaughter in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595972","Home Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-17T18:09:18.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595972/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595972/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-07","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people received pre-charge bail conditions that (a) withheld their travel documents and (b) restricted their movement in each year since 2010; and how many people breached those pre-charge bail conditions.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595973","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-14","<p>Information on whether or not a defendant is in attendance at their hearing is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","47077","2016-10-14T12:22:43.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595973/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595973/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people prosecuted in their absence were on bail in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","47079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595974","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-14","<p>Data on indeterminate sentence prisoners (both those serving life and Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP) sentences) are routinely published as part of the Offender management statistics quarterly bulletin, and can be found on GOV.UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-14T11:40:28.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595974/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595974/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners are serving indefinite sentences in England.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","46736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595975","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Tackling bad practices by claims management companies (CMCs) is a priority for the Government. Action already taken includes the removal of over a thousand CMC licenses since 2010 and the issuing of over £2 million in fines.</p><p> </p><p>Collaborative work between the Claims Management Regulation Unit and other regulators has resulted in the successful disruption and prosecution of criminal operations by CMCs engaged in fraudulent and illegitimate claims.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T15:42:24.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595975/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595975/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to tackle illegitimate and fraudulent activity by claims handling companies.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","46734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595976","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-18","<p>On 11<sup>th</sup> October 2016 there were 215 indeterminate sentence prisoners on the referral list for the Healthy Sex Programme and 115 for the Extended Sexual Offending Treatment Programme in England and Wales. All other NOMS accredited offending behaviour programmes are managed locally, and data on waiting lists is not held centrally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-18T09:36:09.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595976/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595976/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners serving indefinite sentences in England are awaiting re-offending courses.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","46737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595977","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Ministry of Justice is finalising the one year post implementation review of the Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013 and a decision will be made about publication in due course.</p><p> </p><p>It is considering the further reviews.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","47401","2016-10-17T12:16:41.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595977/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595977/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department plans to conduct a three and five year post-implementation review of the Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595978","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-18","<p>This data is not centrally recorded and could only be obtained by incurring disproportionate costs.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-18T12:46:32.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595978/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595978/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of domestic abuse victims in child contact cases in the family court have been in receipt of legal aid in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","46936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595979","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-18","<p>The number of civilian enforcement officers that were employed by HM Courts and Tribunals Service since 2013 are:-</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Headcount</p></td><td><p>FTE (Full time Equivalent)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2013</p></td><td><p>296</p></td><td><p>287.49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2014</p></td><td><p>242</p></td><td><p>231.18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2015</p></td><td><p>212</p></td><td><p>202.59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>185</p></td><td><p>173.72</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data prior to 2013 could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>HMCTS takes recovery and enforcement of financial impositions very seriously and is working to ensure that clamping down on defaulters is a continued priority nationwide and remains committed to finding new ways to ensure impositions are paid and to trace those who do not pay. This is why there has been a year on year increase in the total amount of financial penalties collected over the last five years. The amount of money collected has risen from £310m at the end of 2014/115 to a record of £381 million at the end of 2015/16.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-18T09:26:10.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595979/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595979/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","HM Courts and Tribunals Service: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many civilian enforcement officers were employed by HM Courts and Tribunal Service in each year since 2010; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","46842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595980","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government remains committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015. We are continuing to consider its implementation carefully whilst also considering our other justice priorities.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-17T15:49:53.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595980/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595980/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44657, for what reasons the commencement of Section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 has not yet taken place.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595981","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-12","<p>As the Chancellor set out on 13 August, all structural and investment fund projects signed before the Autumn Statement will be fully funded, even when these projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-12T16:46:18.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595981/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595981/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Offenders: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether all European funding for schemes to improve the employability of prisoners has been protected for the duration of their funding period.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","46967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595982","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-12","<p>There were 33 incidents relating to drones reported by prisons in 2015. This includes finds, interceptions and sightings of drones in and around prisons in England and Wales. The Ministry of Justice intends to routinely publish information on prison drone incidents in the future and 2016 data will be provided in due course as part of the publication schedule.</p><p> </p><p>We remain vigilant to all incidents involving drones and take the threat they pose to prison security very seriously. A range of methods to counter the threat posed by drones are being trialled and evaluated for their effectiveness across the prison estate. We have already introduced new legislation to further strengthen our powers, making it illegal to land a drone in prison or to use a drone to drop in contraband. Anyone found using a drone in an attempt to get contraband into prisons can be punished with a sentence of up to two years imprisonment. We take a zero tolerance approach to smuggling of contraband into prisons and work closely with the police and Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) to ensure those caught are prosecuted.</p><p> </p><p>Note: All figures have been drawn from live administrative data systems. Care is taken when processing and analysing the returns, but the detail collected is subject to the inaccuracies inherent in any large scale recording system.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-12T16:49:39.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595982/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595982/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Prisons: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many drones have been intercepted operating over prisons in England and Wales (a) in 2015 and (b) from January 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","46968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595983","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-02","<p>The law requires the welfare of the child to be the court’s paramount concern when making any decision about a child’s upbringing, including with whom the child is to live or spend time.</p><p> </p><p>Any person who is a party to such proceedings will provide initial evidence and information to the court in their original application or in any response to an application. A party may make representations to the court about any further evidence they wish to put before the court. Rules of court indicate that it is for the court to determine how and when parties may submit evidence. The rules provide for different ways in which this can be done, including a party giving evidence in writing, orally or via video link facilities, where available.</p><p> </p><p>In child arrangements proceedings, the court may also ask the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (Cafcass) to provide independent analysis and recommendations.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-02T16:38:58.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595983/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595983/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Children: Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of the opportunities to present evidence in child custody cases; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","46956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595984","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>This Government is committed to supporting vulnerable people at court, including victims of domestic abuse. The family courts take the issue of domestic abuse extremely seriously. There is a strong and clear framework for judges to apply to the management of difficult court room situations, to ensure they are handled sensitively for alleged victims of domestic abuse and other vulnerable witnesses. All judges receive specific training on this framework and they can intervene to prevent inappropriate questions or have questions relayed. Practical protections, for example, protective screens, video links, separate waiting rooms and separate entrances are available where appropriate. The Government is working with the judiciary to consider what additional protections may be necessary.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-09T12:05:41.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595984/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595984/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to protect victims of domestic abuse in family law courts.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","46920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595985","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:10:40.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595985/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595985/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Ministry of Justice: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of staff on the payroll of her Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595986","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not employ cleaning staff. Cleaning of the Ministry of Justice’s estate is outsourced. The contract requires that all contracted staff have undergone the necessary pre-employment checks and have the right to work in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:03:40.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595986/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595986/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Ministry of Justice: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of her Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595987","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>These two pieces of data are not comparable. Question 43488 refers to the Crown and Magistrates’ courts specifically, and family courts were not included. We are clear that security in the family courts is taken extremely seriously and we have robust arrangements in place to protect court users.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:15:06.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595987/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595987/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43488, what the reason is for the discrepancy between the figure provided in that answer and data in recent research published by Women's Aid on 13 September 2016 on the proportion of survivors of domestic abuse that had access to a separate waiting room in the family court.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","47301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595988","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Ministry of Justice is finalising the one year post implementation review of the Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013 and a decision will be made about publication in due course.</p><p> </p><p>It is considering the further reviews.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","46871","2016-10-17T12:16:41.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595988/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595988/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the one-year post-implementation review of the Taking Control of Goods Regulations 2013 has been completed; and if she will make the outcome of that review available to hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","47401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595989","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Ministers are considering this issue and the Government will bring forward proposals in the coming months.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","47376","2016-10-17T16:18:32.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595989/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595989/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Small Claims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what preparatory work is currently underway in her Department on the consultation on increasing the small claims limit from £1,000 to £5,000.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","47375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595990","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>Ministers are considering this issue and the Government will bring forward proposals in the coming months.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","47375","2016-10-17T16:18:32.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595990/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595990/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Small Claims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 3.103 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, when her Department plans to launch the consultation on increasing the small claims limit from £1,000 to £5,000.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","47376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595991","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer to PQ 44155.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:41:38.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595991/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595991/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Gender Recognition Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department has plans to bring forward proposals to amend the legislation requiring statutory declarations to be dated within six months of the date of the Gender Recognition Certificate application.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","47439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595992","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>HMCTS are considering a range of options about how best to deliver this service. The tender process will allow HMCTS to make informed decisions about what is in the best interests of the service and the taxpayer. No decision on the way forward for the Civilian Enforcement Office role has been made at the current time.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T16:38:32.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595992/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595992/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans her Department has for civilian enforcement officers within the context of its plans to outsource work to the private sector.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","47362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595993","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-17","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-17T15:32:58.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595993/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595993/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Ministry of Justice: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of the staff employed by her Department are non-UK nationals.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595994","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) has issued advice that Miracle Mineral Solution (MMS) is not safe and should not be sold for human consumption. It has been working with local authorities across the country to share knowledge, investigate and disrupt the sale of MMS and other similar products.</p><p> </p><p>The FSA’s National Food Crime Unit has secured the removal of MMS products from major marketplace websites, and has shared information internationally through the National Crime Agency, alerting authorities in specific countries to the risks relating to known proponents of the use of MMS in this manner.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, the Government has no plans to bring forward legislation in this area.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-19T15:02:58.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595994/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595994/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-07","Miracle Mineral Solution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to enable the prosecution of people who promote the use of miracle mineral solution as a cure for autism.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","47521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595995","Leader of the House","false","2016-10-18","<p>As of 13 October, there is a total of three hundred and sixty eight (368) Peers with desks provided within one hundred and twelve (112) offices in the Palace of Westminster.</p><p>There is a total of twenty eight (28) desks provided within eight (8) offices to Civil Servants in the House of Commons foot print of the Palace of Westminster for the following: Prime Minister, Home Secretary, Leader of the House and Government Chief Whip.</p><p>There is a total of twenty one (21) desks provided within six (6) offices to Civil Servants in the House of Lords foot print of the Palace of Westminster for the following: Cabinet Office (16 desks, 4 offices) and Crown Office (5 desks, 2 Offices). In addition there is a Bill Team Room in the House of Lords. This is a single office with two desks which is for the use of civil servants from whichever department is having legislation debated in the Chamber to use as a ‘hotdesking’ facility.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-10-18T15:21:58.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595995/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595995/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-10-07","Palace of Westminster: Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, how many (a) Peers and (b) civil servants have offices within the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595996","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>My Department does not directly employ any cleaning staff within the Westminster estate, we utilise contracted services provided by HM Treasury.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-17T11:26:19.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595996/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595996/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-07","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of his Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595997","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-10-14T12:48:41.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595997/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595997/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-07","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what proportion of staff on the payroll of his Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595998","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government committed, in our manifesto, to work to reform the system of legacy inquests in a way that enables the UK Government to fulfil its international obligations. The current system was not designed to cope with a large number of highly complex cases that involve sensitive information. Since taking up office I have been meeting regularly with the Executive parties and a large number of other stakeholders as part of work to progress reforms around legacy issues. I will continue to engage with the Northern Ireland Executive and others and consider any proposals that the Executive puts forward that would lead to effective reform of the inquest system.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-12T14:17:35.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595998/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595998/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-07","Army: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions he has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on funding for inquests into the killings allegedly carried out by the British Army's Military Reaction Force.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","46959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595999","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The issue of milk bank sharing is a devolved matter and as such falls to the Department of Health in Northern Ireland. However, the UK Government’s focus remains on making a success of exiting the European Union and getting the right deal both for Northern Ireland and the UK as a whole.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-10-14T12:03:44.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595999/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/595999/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-07","Milk: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what arrangements he plans to put in place for milk bank sharing between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","47199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596000","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-17","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy did not attend the September 2016 G20 meeting.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-17T09:34:19.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596000/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596000/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-07","Nuclear Power Stations: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with President Xi at the September 2016 G20 meeting on separating the building of the Hualong One reactor at Bradwell from the agreement on Hinkley Point C.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","46701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596001","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-13","<p>All companies and other organisations that provide a service to the public are legally obliged under the Equality Act 2010 to ensure no race discrimination occurs. The Race Disparity Audit was set up to identify and analyse racial disparities in public services, working with data from Government departments and their arm’s length bodies to build a complete and accurate picture across the country. This is a unique and ambitious undertaking and there are no current plans to extend it beyond public services.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-10-13T09:12:43.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596001/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596001/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-07","Consumers: Racial Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will extend the proposed audit of public services to reveal racial disparities to all organisations and companies which provide (a) car insurance and (b) other consumer services required by law.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","47432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596002","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>Following the EU Referendum, the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, Lord Dunlop, and I have met with Scottish Government Ministers on a number of occasions, including with the new Scottish Government Minister for UK Negotiations on Scotland’s Place in Europe, Mr Michael Russell.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to work with the Scottish Government as we form our negotiating strategy, working closely to get the best possible deal for all parts of the United Kingdom as we leave the European Union.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-14T10:03:53.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596002/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596002/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on the result of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","47274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596003","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly; all staff that join do so on an assignment, loan or secondment from other Government bodies, who remain the employers.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-14T10:06:54.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596003/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596003/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what proportion of staff on the payroll of his Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596004","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Scotland Office participates in a Ministry of Justice Framework Contract for the cleaning of its premises in the Westminster estate. The Scotland Office does not hold information as to the nationality of the staff employed through this contract.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-14T10:05:37.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596004/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596004/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of his Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596005","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>I meet my Rt hon Friend the Home Secretary regularly and we discuss a wide range of issues.</p><p>The Tier 4 visa pilot is part of the Home Office’s continued efforts to ensure that the UK maintains an excellent offer to attract the brightest and best to study at our world-leading institutions. Its main aim is to help simplify the visa application process for international students looking to study on a Masters’ course, in the UK, of 13 months or less. It will also help to support students who wish to switch into a work route and take up a graduate role by extending the leave period following the end of their study to up to six months. The pilot does not make any changes to the Tier 2 visa route and is not a return to the post-study work visa route, which we closed in April 2012 due to high levels of abuse.</p><p> </p><p>The institutions taking part in the pilot were chosen due to their consistently low level of visa refusals. It is a fundamental requirement of Tier 4 that education institutions who recruit international students take responsibility for them. This means the institution must ensure the student is genuine and meets the requirements of the Immigration Rules, before assigning them a Confirmation of Acceptance for Studies (CAS), as well as ensuring that the student leaves the UK at the end of his or her studies.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-14T10:08:50.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596005/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596005/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for the Home Department on the inclusion of Scottish universities in the post-study work visa pilot.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","46838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596006","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>I spoke to Sir Julian King in August to discuss his nomination to the post of UK Commissioner to the European Commission (EC). Sir Julian was at the time the nominee for that post. He has since been confirmed as both the UK Commissioner to the EC and as the Commissioner for the Security Union.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-12T14:14:53.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596006/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596006/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Scotland Office: European Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which EU Commissioners he has met since 23 June 2016; and when and where such meetings took place.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","47143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596007","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>We have made significant progress since the Scotland Act 2016 reached Royal Assent in March 2016 and a large number of provisions of the Act are already in force, giving the Scottish Parliament responsibilities in new policy areas. Most recently, new welfare powers came into force on 5 September 2016 and the Joint Ministerial Working Group on Welfare continues to meet to discuss the implementation of welfare powers, as well as the commencement and implementation of remaining welfare provisions.</p><p>Implementation dates for a number of the tax and fiscal responsibilities in the Scotland Act 2016 are set out in the Fiscal Framework for Scotland.</p><p>We are working constructively with the Scottish Government on the commencement of sections of the Scotland Act 2016 and I will meet regularly with Derek Mackay MSP, Cabinet Secretary for Finance and the Constitution in the Scottish Government, to discuss progress. I will ensure the UK Parliament is kept informed about this important work.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-14T10:10:34.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596007/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596007/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-07","Scotland Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, when he plans to give effect to the provisions of the Scotland Act 2016 not yet in force.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","47025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596008","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>Advice on “First aid on the road” is contained in Annex 7 of The Highway Code. Driver’s knowledge of first aid is tested as part of the driver theory test and many professional drivers take first aid training. The Department is providing support for a not-for-profit training programme for drivers in administering first aid.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T09:22:48.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596008/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596008/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Driving: First Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the report by the British Red Cross, entitled Are pre-hospital deaths from trauma and accidental injury preventable?, published in September 2016, what steps he is taking to ensure that first aid education is included in the Government's road safety strategy.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","46989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596009","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Highway authorities have a duty under Section 41 of the Highways Act 1980 to ensure, so far as is reasonably practicable, that safe passage along a highway is not endangered by snow or ice. Winter service and maintenance is therefore the sole responsibility of the respective highway authority. This includes ensuring they have adequate road grit supplies.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport continues to take action to ensure the country enters the 2016/17 winter season well prepared. This includes monitoring road grit being held around the country throughout the winter season, working closely with the UK domestic road grit producers, continuing to maintain a substantial national emergency road grit reserve and having a robust distribution process in place, if for any reason this road grit is needed to be allocated.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is also currently undertaking a survey of highway authorities to determine how much road grit is available in the UK for the forthcoming 2016-17 winter. However from previous surveys, we anticipate the country has over one million tonnes of road grit at its disposal, which is in addition to the 383,000 tonnes held as part of the national emergency grit reserve.</p><p> </p><p>It is for each highway authority to ensure that they have adequate road grit procured to treat the roads for which they are responsible, as required. The costs fall to each highway authority. These costs may vary depending on the road grit supplier and the distance the grit has to be hauled to the depots. The typical cost of road grit, including mining, storage and distribution lies within the range of £30 to £38 per tonne.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T12:34:33.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596009/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596009/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Roads: Snow and Ice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much road grit is available in the UK for the 2016-17 winter; and how much the (a) mining, (b) storage and (c) distribution of road grit costs per year.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","47013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596010","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>Under the Mersey Tunnels Act 2004, the power to set tolls for the Mersey Tunnels is vested in the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority, who own and operate the Tunnels. The Combined Authority has already reduced the cost of tolls to fast tag users and will consider its strategic approach further, to inform the forthcoming report on its Review of tolls. This Review will inform the decision on future toll levels, which will be taken locally by the Combined Authority, as required by the Mersey Tunnels Act.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T10:15:48.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596010/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596010/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Mersey Tunnels: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to comments made by the former Chancellor of the Exchequer at a meeting in Birkenhead on 4 May 2015 and pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2016 to Question 45786, whether he plans to directly intervene in the review of the Mersey tunnel tolls to reduce the cost of those tolls.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","46998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596011","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The draft Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy sets out the Government’s plans for increasing cycling and walking in England. It is a high level document, with a long term ambition up to 2040, supported by a target and a number of objectives.</p><p> </p><p>The Strategy outlines how Government will work with local bodies and business to develop expertise and support, the tools and policies Government will deliver to support them in increasing walking and cycling in local communities, and how this work will enable progress towards our national objectives and target. It does not set out details of individual schemes as that is a matter for local bodies.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T15:38:34.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596011/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596011/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","River Thames: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the cycling and walking investment strategy will include investment for the proposed cycling and pedestrian bridge linking Rotherhithe to Canary Wharf.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","46996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596012","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Road Safety Statement, published in December last year, sets out the Government’s priorities for improving road safety over this Parliament.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T10:45:48.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596012/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596012/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the rate of road traffic accidents.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","47119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596013","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State has not met with Great Western Railway or South West Trains on the provision of Wi-Fi services.</p><p> </p><p>On all Department for Transport-controlled rail franchises, in England and Wales, free Wi-Fi is being introduced. All train operators bidding for new franchises and direct award agreements will have to present a phased implementation plan for free Wi-Fi.</p><p> </p><p>As of July 2016, 25% of passenger journeys operating within the DfT controlled franchises have Wi-Fi available. We forecast 90% of passenger journeys will benefit from free Wi-Fi by the end of 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:58:28.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596013/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596013/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with (a) Great Western Railway and (b) South West Trains on the provision of wifi services on those trains.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","47325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596014","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The fee charged when paying vehicle excise duty (VED) by credit card is to meet the costs of processing credit card payments. The fee is provided for in the Road Vehicles (Payment of Duty by Credit Card) (Prescribed Fee) Regulations 2005. The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) must comply with HM Treasury’s “Managing Public Money” guidance and recover costs from those who use its services.</p><p> </p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) regularly reviews all the fees and charges it makes for the services it provides, including the fee incurred when paying vehicle excise duty (VED) using a credit card. Paying VED using a debit card is free of charge. Customers can also pay for VED by cash, cheque or debit card at a Post Office® and direct debit is now offered as an additional way for people to pay their VED.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-17T12:18:34.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596014/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596014/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to remove or reduce the fee incurred when paying vehicle excise duty via credit card.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","47219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596015","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government will publish the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study, and its response to the recommendations, in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T10:36:49.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596015/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596015/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","London-Brighton Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 906370, if he will publish the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study; whether he plans to fund proposals for a Brighton Mainline 2 in order to remedy the significant capacity and performance constraints identified; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","46898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596016","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>This Government is committing a total of £15.2 billion in the enhancement and long-term maintenance of the Strategic Road Network between 2015/16 and 2020/21 including 127 major schemes. Of these there are 42 schemes for the North of England with a value of £2.9 billion investment.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>On the local road network, we have been providing significant investment for roads in the North. This includes eight schemes completed including the Crewe Green Link Road, five under construction including the Heysham-M6 Link Road and the Mersey Gateway Bridge, as well as a further five which are under development. In addition we are currently considering further bids for development funding for large schemes on the local network, including the A6 to M60 Relief Road Scheme. These bids are currently being assessed and the successful schemes will be announced in the autumn.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T15:02:10.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596016/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596016/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Roads: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has for road investment in the north of England.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","46897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596017","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Under section 16 of the Transport Act 1985 local licensing authorities outside of London have the power to limit the number of licensed Hackney carriages if they are satisfied that there is no significant demand for the services of Hackney carriages (within the area to which the licence would apply) which is unmet. There are no powers to restrict the number of Hackney carriages in London or private hire vehicles in or outside of London and the Government has no plans to introduce any such legislation at this time.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T10:49:53.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596017/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596017/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to introduce a limit to the number of Hackney carriage and private hire driver licences local authorities can issue.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","46927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596018","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>I can confirm we have received such applications, and we are currently considering them.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:51:38.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596018/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596018/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department received applications from Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) to activate the force majeure clause in the franchise agreement for Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern passenger rail services since July 2015.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596019","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State has a duty under Section 30 of the Railways Act 1993, to maintain the continuity of passenger rail services in the event that a passenger rail franchise terminates and is not immediately replaced. In order to ensure the effective discharge of this duty the Department maintains a standby capability which would enable it to step into a rail franchise and operate it in the public sector should the need arise. There are currently no plans in place to step into the Thameslink Southern and Great Northern franchise.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:48:41.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596019/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596019/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department plans to put in place for an operator of last report for the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern passenger rail franchise since September 2013.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596020","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>There are a number of provisions throughout each franchise agreement that relate to the continuity and preservation of rail services by a Successor Operator which could include the Operator of Last Resort under the provisions of Section 30 of the Railways Act 1993. Schedules 1.6, 10, 14 and 15 of the National Rail Franchise Terms and Conditions are of particular relevance in this regard.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:42:28.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596020/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596020/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the operator of last report provisions are for each franchise agreement for passenger rail services currently in operation.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596021","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>We plan to consult later this year on changes to the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation including steps to provide more long term confidence for producers and to address indirect land use change with options to limit the contribution from crop based biofuels.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","47492","2016-10-12T16:02:48.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596021/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596021/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Biofuels: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to launch its consultation on biofuels; and whether that consultation will address the issues of indirect land use and level of the crop cap.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","46965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596022","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>On 1 September the Secretary of State announced a Network Rail £20m fund, to help improve resilience of the Southern network. Chris Gibb will head a new project board, working with the train operator, the Department for Transport and Network Rail, to explore how to achieve a rapid improvement to services for the public. The board will oversee the fund and create closer working between Govia Thameslink Railway and Network Rail to improve performance.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:55:20.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596022/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596022/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent steps his Department has taken to improve the service on Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Chris Philp","Croydon South","Chris Philp","46974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596023","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State intends to make an announcement about the remainder of the HS2 route, including the Manchester junction, later this autumn.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T15:33:39.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596023/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596023/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans that the Northern Chord at the Manchester junction will be retained in the route of HS2.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","46942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596024","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State regularly meets Network Rail to discuss a wide range of topics. Network Rail have recently published an update of the Enhancement Delivery Programme on 30 September 2016. The North of England Programme (which includes the electrification timetable) is on page 11 on the following link: <a href="https://www.networkrail.co.uk/Enhancements-Delivery-Plan-Sept-2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.networkrail.co.uk/Enhancements-Delivery-Plan-Sept-2016.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T10:30:08.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596024/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596024/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Network Rail on the rail electrification programme in the North West; and if he will publish a revised timetable for that work.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596025","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>Transport for the North are leading the development of a number of potential options for Northern Powerhouse Rail, including options that make use of sections of the HS2 network.</p><p> </p><p>Should Northern Powerhouse Rail be integrated directly with sections of the HS2 network, the rolling stock will be specified to operate on HS2 infrastructure.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T15:30:30.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596025/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596025/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Northern: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Northern Powerhouse Rail rolling stock will be permitted to operate on HS2 infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","46948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596026","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>No such assessment has been made of this operational matter. The publication of the Weekly Operating Notice is for Network Rail and the train and freight companies to manage.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:55:55.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596026/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596026/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Network Rail: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of Network Rail's administrative performance in providing weekly operating and signalling notices to train drivers and other rail staff.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596027","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The contract for IEP sets out the process for calculating any liquidated damages the Secretary of State would be liable to pay to Agility Trains in the event that the trains cannot be introduced in line with the contracted schedule for delivery and operation. This would be calculated as a function of the daily Set Availability Payment forgone at that time. The precise amount would remain commercially confidential.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:03:41.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596027/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596027/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Agility Trains: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much compensation his Department is liable for in its contract with Agility Trains in the event that the Inter City Express (IEP) fleet cannot be introduced in line with the contracted schedule for (a) delivery and (b) operation of new IEP trains on the (i) Great Western and (ii) East Coast mainlines.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596028","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-13","<p>The number of government-owned (freehold) goods vehicle test stations are as follows;</p><p>(a) 40 in England (b) 3 in Wales and (c) 12 in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-13T10:04:29.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596028/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596028/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Motor Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many government-owned goods vehicle test stations are based in (a) England, (b) Wales and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","46711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596029","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The British Transport Police Authority, which oversees the British Transport Police, includes a member who has knowledge of the interests of persons in Wales and who is appointed following consultation with the National Assembly for Wales. There are no plans to change these accountability arrangements insofar as they relate to policing of the railways in Wales.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:14:58.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596029/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596029/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","British Transport Police: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether British Transport Police officers based in Wales will continue to be accountable to his Department after the devolution of the rail franchise to the Welsh Assembly.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","46712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596030","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>I published the Road Safety Statement in December 2015 which sets out the measures Government is taking to improve road safety including the reduction of road traffic offences. Our award-winning THINK! campaigns have also been running throughout the year to educate drivers on the risk and consequences of a number of different type of offences. The Department is in regular contact with a range of organisations and their reports, such as the ‘RAC Report on Motoring 2016’, are provided to the Department. The Department often includes research evidence in its impact assessments, for example the Elvik ‘dose response’ model, which shows that rigorous enforcement increases the deterrent effect on offending. The Government continues to keep road safety and road traffic offences under review.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","46715 ; 46718","2016-10-14T11:01:21.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596030/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596030/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce (a) dangerous driving and (b) driving under the influence of alcohol.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","46714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596031","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>I published the Road Safety Statement in December 2015 which sets out the measures Government is taking to improve road safety including the reduction of road traffic offences. Our award-winning THINK! campaigns have also been running throughout the year to educate drivers on the risk and consequences of a number of different type of offences. The Department is in regular contact with a range of organisations and their reports, such as the ‘RAC Report on Motoring 2016’, are provided to the Department. The Department often includes research evidence in its impact assessments, for example the Elvik ‘dose response’ model, which shows that rigorous enforcement increases the deterrent effect on offending. The Government continues to keep road safety and road traffic offences under review.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","46714 ; 46718","2016-10-14T11:01:21.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596031/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596031/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations his Department has received on the effectiveness of the laws against dangerous driving, speeding and driving while under the influence of alcohol in deterring those offences.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","46715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596032","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>There is no central national record of the enrolment of volunteer Coastguard Rescue Officers as enrolment is conducted locally at the 340 Coastguard Rescue Teams in the UK, as the need arises.</p><p> </p><p>To provide the information in the format you have requested would be at disproportionate cost to the taxpayer.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:28:53.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596032/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596032/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Rescue Services: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many volunteer coastguards were recruited by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596033","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The number of Coastguards employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each year since 2010/11 is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>517</p></td><td><p>491</p></td><td><p>469</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>386</p></td><td><p>416</p></td><td><p>424</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>When interpreting the above numbers, it is important to note that the new HM Coastguard structure enables the National Maritime Operations Centre (NMOC) and nine Coastguard Operation Centres (CGOC) to coordinate any incident around the UK coast. Workload and incidents continue to managed locally but all Coastguard Centres now have a national support network available to them during busy periods. These arrangements are most effectively deployed from a smaller national footprint.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:32:43.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596033/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596033/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Maritime and Coastguard Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many coastguards were employed by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596034","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>I published the Road Safety Statement in December 2015 which sets out the measures Government is taking to improve road safety including the reduction of road traffic offences. Our award-winning THINK! campaigns have also been running throughout the year to educate drivers on the risk and consequences of a number of different type of offences. The Department is in regular contact with a range of organisations and their reports, such as the ‘RAC Report on Motoring 2016’, are provided to the Department. The Department often includes research evidence in its impact assessments, for example the Elvik ‘dose response’ model, which shows that rigorous enforcement increases the deterrent effect on offending. The Government continues to keep road safety and road traffic offences under review.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","46714 ; 46715","2016-10-14T11:01:21.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596034/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596034/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research his Department has undertaken on the effects on road safety of adopting harsher sentencing for those who break the law by dangerous driving, speeding or driving whilst under the influence of alcohol.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","46718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596035","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard’s Volunteer Coastguard Rescue Teams are appropriately trained and so can be deployed for any incident on beaches or at the coast. The Maritime and Coastguard Agency continually monitors the local provision of this capability.</p><p> </p><p>Safety at public beaches, and specifically the provision of lifeguarding services, is generally the responsibility of the local authority, who carry out risk assessments to determine appropriate safety measures.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:36:05.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596035/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596035/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Rescue Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate has been made of the (a) coastguard and (b) lifeguard capacity on UK (i) beaches and (ii) coastal waters.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596036","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Prior to the re-launch of the Franchising Programme in spring 2013, the costs of different franchising projects were not individually recorded.</p><p> </p><p>The cost of each re-franchising project since the re-launch is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Franchise</p></td><td><p>Cost (£M)</p></td><td><p>Notes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Essex Thameside</p></td><td><p>4.815</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thameslink, Southern &amp; Great Northern</p></td><td><p>7.288</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Coast</p></td><td><p>8.429</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern</p></td><td><p>8.668 (to date)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>TransPennine Express</p></td><td><p>7.577 (to date)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Anglia</p></td><td><p>7.413 (to date)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures include adviser costs (financial, technical and legal advisers), pay costs for the project team, “non-pay” costs (such as bidder day seminars, public consultations, etc), and VAT where applicable, for the duration of the procurements.</p><p> </p><p>The (admin) sums invested in competent staff and advisors are dwarfed by the (Resource) SPRS benefits to the Department – £200 for every pound spent.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes</strong></p><p> </p><p>NOTE 1: The Essex Thameside figure represents the work done after the relaunch of the Franchising Programme. There was a significant amount of work completed prior to the pausing of the programme in autumn 2012 which is not included here.</p><p> </p><p>NOTE 2: The costs for the refranchising of the Intercity East Coast Franchise were not charged to the public purse, but were covered by the Performance Bond that National Express put forward following its default of the previous East Coast contract.</p><p> </p><p>NOTE 3: The figures for Northern, TransPennine Express (TPE) and East Anglia are the latest figures (as at the end of August 2016). East Anglia is still a ‘live’ project. Whilst Northern and TPE have concluded, there are still some residual costs that may affect the final figures.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:34:11.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596036/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596036/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to his Department was of each re-tendering exercise held for franchises for (a) long distance and (b) regional passenger rail services in each year since 2005-06.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596037","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Invitation to Tender for the West Midlands franchise allows bidders to propose alternative layouts which could include fewer seats and more standing space for services which operate on the 'Cross-City' line in Birmingham. This option is included in response to the West Midlands franchise consultation, where there was a particularly strong response from respondents that use this line about changing the current 3+2 seating arrangement to provide wider aisles and more spacious and comfortable standing areas. However, if bidders do propose changes to the seating layouts, they would need to meet certain criteria for this to be permissible.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:59:50.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596037/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596037/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether bidders for the next West Midlands regional rail franchise will be able to remove seats from rolling stock in order to increase passenger carrying capacity; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596038","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>We expect potential bidders for the next Inter City West Coast (ICWC) franchise to plan their train services to meet the needs of their passengers and the wider network. To make sure the Department’s specification best reflects the needs of the passengers and stakeholders of the franchise a public consultation on the franchise was run from 10 May to 2 August this year. This sought the public’s and stakeholders’ views and priorities on a number of areas of the franchise specification. The consultation acknowledged that capacity for additional train services on the West Coast Mainline is limited and sought views on how the franchise could cater for growth.</p><p> </p><p>The responses will help inform us about what we will ask for in the tender documents from the future franchise operator and will be provided to bidders for the franchise to inform their responses. We are now reviewing and analysing the consultation responses and will publish a summary in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:41:53.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596038/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596038/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","West Coast Railway Line: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to increase passenger carrying capacity on Inter City West Coast services between cities in the West Midlands.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596039","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Ministers have held no discussions with the Train Operating Companies since the launch of the fund and do not expect to do so before the closing date of 25 November 2016.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:45:32.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596039/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596039/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railway Stations: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with train operating companies on the New Stations Fund launched on 26 August 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596040","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Currently, the method of train dispatch for incidents at the platform train interface is not recorded so the data requested is not available. However, a new Safety Management Information System is being introduced in December 2016, which is designed to enable the industry to dig deeper into the trends behind incidents.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:51:17.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596040/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596040/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many platform train interface incidents that were reported on the national rail network in each year since 2010 involved driver-only operated passenger services.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596041","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department issued the Invitation to Tender (ITT) for the West Midlands franchise on 30 August 2016, and bidders have until 29 November 2016 to submit their bids. The Department intends to follow the risk adjustment process as detailed in the published ITT once bids have been received.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is evaluating bids for the South Western rail franchise and intends to follow the risk adjustment process as detailed in Appendix 3 to the Invitation to Tender, published on the Department’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The East Anglia franchise competition concluded on 23 August, when the Department signed the Franchise Agreement with Abellio East Anglia. The Department followed the risk adjustment process detailed in the Invitation to Tender, published on the Department’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not communicate the detail of Risk Adjustments, as these relate to cost and revenue details of the leading bid, which are commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:12:03.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596041/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596041/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether risk adjustments have been made to the rail passenger franchises currently out to tender for services on the (a) South Western, (b) West Midlands and (c) East Anglia lines since 23 June 2016; and if he will provide details of any such adjustments in each case.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596042","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Government recognises the importance of accessible transport to all young people and, whilst there are no plans to introduce a statutory concession for young people, we are working with the sector to encourage operators to continue to improve their offers.</p><p> </p><p>In the de-regulated bus market it is for operators to set their own fares. Current estimates indicate that 50% of young people aged 16 to 19 receive at least a third off standard fares.</p><p> </p><p>The new Enhanced Partnership powers in the Bus Services Bill would allow local transport authorities and bus operators to agree standard ticket rules, such as eligibility for half fares across operators.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T12:47:18.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596042/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596042/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Public Transport: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has any plans to extend child discounts on public transport from 16 to 18 years to match the new compulsory school leaving age.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","46732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596043","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>These dates will not be announced by the Department for Transport. Network Rail is reviewing the options available for deployment of Traffic Management in Wales and will communicate the decision once it has been made.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:07:27.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596043/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596043/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Network Rail: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce the dates for the (a) planned commissioning, (b) delivery of contracted functionality and (c) installation of the first deployment traffic management system for the Rail Operating Centre at Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596044","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold this level of detail on Network Rail’s costs.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T10:44:43.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596044/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596044/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Network Rail: Thales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost of the contract between Network Rail and Thales has been by heading for the supply of two first deployment traffic management systems for rail operating centres at (a) Cardiff and (b) Romford since the award of that contract.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596045","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>The government has no current plans to extend the home to school statutory entitlement beyond the age of 16.</p><p> </p><p>It is helpful to be clear initially that young people do not need to be in school beyond the age of 16. There are a range of ways that young people can fulfil their duty to participate in education and training until they are 18, as well as staying at school. Options include apprenticeships or part-time paid work together with study.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory responsibility for transport to education and training for 16 to 19 year olds remains with local authorities, enabling them to make decisions and arrangements which best match local needs and circumstances. Arrangements do not have to include free or subsidised travel; however, local authorities are expected to make reasonable decisions based on the needs of their population, the local transport infrastructure and the resources they have available.</p><p> </p><p>Most 16 to 19 year olds have access to a discount or concession on local travel, from their local transport provider, their local authority, or from their education or training provider. Providers can also use the 16-19 Bursary Fund to support young people with the costs associated with attending education or training. This is often used to support transport for disadvantaged young people.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-01T13:17:08.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596045/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596045/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-07","Schools: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she has any plans to extend her Department's policy of free school transport for children between eight and 16 years old living over three miles from their school to match the compulsory school leaving age of 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","46733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596046","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Government is committed to building transport networks that work for everyone, including ensuring that disabled people have the same travel choices as other members of society.</p><p> </p><p>Taxis and Private Hire Vehicles (PHVs) provide a particularly important service for many disabled people and it is therefore vital that their drivers have the knowledge and skills to provide appropriate assistance whenever it is required.</p><p> </p><p>I encourage local licensing authorities to consider how a requirement to undergo disability awareness training might help drivers to feel more confident in providing such assistance, consistent with the authority’s Public Sector Equality Duty.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T11:08:22.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596046/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596046/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that all taxi and minicab drivers undergo disability equality training.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","46880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596047","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Airports Commission shortlisted three airport expansion schemes, two at Heathrow and one at Gatwick. The Government accepted the Commission’s shortlist in December 2015 and is considering all of the evidence, including on noise, very carefully before reaching a view on its preferred scheme.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:21:36.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596047/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596047/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Heathrow Airport: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of noise from Heathrow Airport on people living in the Woking constituency; and if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of an increase in such noise as a result of the construction of a third runway.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","46756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596048","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold statistics related to taxi licences in the format requested. The Department does produce statistics every 2 years on the number of taxi licences issued. The latest statistics show the position as at 31 March 2105 in England and Wales and can be found in table TAXI0104 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/taxi-and-private-hire-vehicles-statistics-england-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/taxi-and-private-hire-vehicles-statistics-england-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The total number of licensed taxis increased by 4.2% to 81,200 since 2013.</p><p>There was a slight drop in the number of taxi only driver licences from 63,200 in 2013 to 62,700 in 2015.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-12T10:39:55.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596048/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596048/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many taxi licences have been issued in each local authority area in each of the past three years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","46806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596049","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>As of 30th September 2016, the Department has purchased a total of 483 properties. The Departments estimate of income from the HS2 Portfolio is circa £7.5m per annum.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-17T12:22:35.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596049/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596049/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many residential properties purchased ahead of the construction of High Speed 2 are being let; and what estimate his Department has made of the total amount it will receive in rent payments from those properties.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","46878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596050","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government has no current plans to use these powers. We have asked the Civil Aviation Authority to update its 2013 review of the impact of environmental landing charges at UK airports to consider the impact of changes since that date.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:58:41.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596050/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596050/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Night Flying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Civil Aviation Authority's review of impact of environmental landing charges published in 2013, if he will exercise his powers under the Civil Aviation Act 1982, Section 78, to direct airports to review their charges for night flights.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","46787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596051","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department does not directly employ any cleaning staff on its Westminster estate. All cleaning staff are employed and managed under outsourced estates and facilities contracts. Information on nationality in such situations is not held by the Department.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:44:04.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596051/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596051/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of his Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596052","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Many staff self-declare their nationality on the staff system. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks and copies of this evidence are held on file for the duration of the person’s employment and for a further two years after they cease working for the department.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:47:37.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596052/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596052/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of staff on the payroll of his Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596053","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>High Speed Two (HS2) Ltd carried out a public consultation on proposals for the HS2 Phase 2 route in 2013 on behalf of the Department for Transport. This contained the location of potential HS2 stations, including South Yorkshire.</p><p> </p><p>Appendix A of the consultation summary report lists the organisations that responded to the consultation:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480397/P2LoR_Ipsos_MORI_FINAL_REPORT.pdf.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480397/P2LoR_Ipsos_MORI_FINAL_REPORT.pdf.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government will make an announcement on the HS2 Phase Two route, of which South Yorkshire is a part, later this year. A public consultation on the route in this area will be issued at the same time as the announcement.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T12:44:21.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596053/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596053/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","High Speed 2 Railway Line: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which organisations his Department has formally consulted on the location of the proposed High Speed 2 station in South Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596054","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The current major works on the A1 from Leeming to Barton in North Yorkshire will result in six permanent gap closures. These gaps will be accessed via a new local road and alternative routes alongside the new motorway for the benefit of the local community. Access to the new motorway will be via a new junction at Catterick and an improved junction at Scotch Corner.</p><p> </p><p>Over the next two months three, maintenance schemes will require temporary gap closures on the A1 at Highfields roundabout, near Berwick; between Lane Head to Old Swarland in Northumberland; and at Buckden (Brampton Rail Bridge) in Cambridgeshire. The affected gaps on the A1 will be re-opened on completion of their respective maintenance works.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:39:41.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596054/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596054/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","A1: Pedestrian Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many crossings across traffic are planned to be closed on the A1 (a) southbound and (b) northbound.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","47266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596055","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The use of the Retail Price Index (RPI) is consistent with the general indexation approach adopted across the rail industry. The Office of Rail and Road uses RPI as the index for Network Rail’s revenues e.g. Track Access Charges. RPI is used widely across Government, including for index linked bonds, vehicle exercise duty, alcohol and tobacco duties, air passenger duty and climate change levies.</p><p> </p><p>It is worth noting that the July 2016 figures for RPI (published on 14 September 2016) and average weekly earnings growth stood at 1.9% and 2.3%, respectively. Each July’s RPI figure is used to set regulated rail fares from January 2nd the following year. On this basis average earnings continue to remain ahead of allowable regulated rail fares increases.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:17:08.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596055/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596055/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45695, on railways: fares, for what reason his Department uses the Retail Price Index as an index for inflation; and if he will consider using a different index for inflation.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596056","Department for Transport","true","2016-10-17","<p><del class="ministerial">The Office of Road &amp; Rail calculates that 97 pence in every pound raised from passenger journeys is spent on running or improving the railway by Network Rail and the Train Operating Companies. Approximately 26 pence in every pound is reinvested through capital enhancements and renewals.<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup></del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial"><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> <a href="http://orr.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/21039/gb-rail-industry-financial-information-2014-15.pdf" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/21039/gb-rail-industry-financial-information-2014-15.pdf</a></del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Rail Delivery Group calculates that 97 pence in every pound raised from passenger journeys is spent on running or improving the railway by Network Rail and the Train Operating Companies. Approximately 26 pence in every pound is reinvested through capital enhancements and renewals.<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup></ins></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial"><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> <a href="http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/times_fares/ticket_types/83871.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/times_fares/ticket_types/83871.aspx</a></ins></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T12:29:57.187Z","2016-11-09T14:42:22.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596056/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596056/answer","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596056/answer/previousversion/14173","Biography information for Paul Maynard","27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45695, what proportion of rail fares paid by passengers are reinvested in the railways by Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596057","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>The revenue raised between the years 2006-07 and 2015-16 through the Railway Safety Levy is set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total (£000)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>16,562</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>17,969</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>19,733</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>18,461</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>17,497</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>17,417</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>15,939</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>15,371</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>15,907</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>154,856</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-12T15:45:50.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596057/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596057/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much revenue the Office for Road and Rail and its predecessor raised through the Railway Safety Levy in each financial year between 2006-07 and 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","46950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596058","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>Many staff self-declare their nationality on the staff system. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks and copies of this evidence are held on file for the duration of the person’s employment and for a further two years after they cease working for the department.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:25:02.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596058/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596058/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Department for Transport: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of the staff employed by his Department are non-UK nationals.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","47421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596059","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-12","<p>We plan to consult later this year on changes to the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation including steps to provide more long term confidence for producers and to address indirect land use change with options to limit the contribution from crop based biofuels.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","46965","2016-10-12T16:02:48.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596059/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Biofuels: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on what date his Department plans to open a consultation on biofuels; and if he will take steps to ensure that that consultation addresses indirect land use change and the level of the crop cap.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","47492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596060","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-13","<p>We are in the process of reviewing the Cycle to Work Scheme guidance published on GOV.UK and are engaging with other Departments, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), HMRC and HMT to get a firmer view on any possible changes that could be made. As part of this review, we will consider the level of the maximum allowance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-13T12:30:33.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596060/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Cycling: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to amend the Cycle to Work scheme to incorporate a higher maximum allowance for disabled cyclists requiring specialist cycles.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","47531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596061","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Government is committed to building transport networks that work for everyone, including ensuring that disabled people have the same travel choices as other members of society.</p><p> </p><p>I am committed to commencing Sections 165 and 167 of the Equality Act, making it unlawful for drivers of wheelchair accessible taxis and Private Hire Vehicles to refuse to provide assistance to passengers in wheelchairs or to charge them extra.</p><p> </p><p>We will shortly be consulting on Regulations regarding the exemption certificates for drivers unable to provide such assistance, and on relevant guidance. We will commence the Sections once the Regulations and guidance are ready for issue.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T12:30:39.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596061/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596061/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when steps have been taken to enact the provisions within section 165 of the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","47530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596062","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government made a formal representation on this issue to the US Department of Transportation on 11 February 2016, which is recorded in the US DoT docket DOT-OST-2015-0261. Ministers and officials continue to make representations on this matter as and when opportunities arise.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-17T14:55:12.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596062/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596062/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Air Routes: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations the Government has made to the US Department of Transportation on progress made on authorising Norwegian Air UK Ltd services from Gatwick and other British airports to the US, as permitted by the EU-US Air Transport Agreement in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","47550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596063","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>Government is committed to building transport networks that work for everyone, including ensuring that disabled people have the same travel choices as other members of society.</p><p> </p><p>Nobody should face discrimination when accessing transport services, and it is unacceptable for any provider to charge a disabled person extra on account of their disability.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Act 2010 requires service providers to make reasonable adjustments to enable disabled people to access their services, and Sections 168 to 173 specifically prevent a taxi or Private Hire Vehicle driver from charging an assistance dog owner extra.</p><p> </p><p>I have also committed to commencing Sections 165 and 167, which will require drivers to provide assistance to passengers in wheelchairs and prevent them from charging more.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-14T10:57:39.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596063/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596063/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps have been taken to prevent taxi drivers charging extra to disabled people.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","47527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596064","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The destination printed on a bus ticket should not have any effect on the amount of reimbursement that the bus operator receives for carrying concessionary passengers.</p><p> </p><p>This is because reimbursement paid to operators is not based on the full commercial adult fare for a typical journey, but on the average equivalent full fare – taken from a “basket of fares” – that each concessionary traveller would have paid in the absence of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Reimbursement payments are also subject to audits of ticket sales data and, if required, ‘on-bus’ surveys of patronage.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","47509","2016-10-14T12:38:22.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596064/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596064/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Bus Services: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of over-staging by bus companies on journeys undertaken using a concessionary bus pass in England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","47508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596065","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-14","<p>The destination printed on a bus ticket should not have any effect on the amount of reimbursement that the bus operator receives for carrying concessionary passengers.</p><p> </p><p>This is because reimbursement paid to operators is not based on the full commercial adult fare for a typical journey, but on the average equivalent full fare – taken from a “basket of fares” – that each concessionary traveller would have paid in the absence of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Reimbursement payments are also subject to audits of ticket sales data and, if required, ‘on-bus’ surveys of patronage.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","47508","2016-10-14T12:38:22.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596065/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596065/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Bus Services: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to (a) educate bus passengers about over-staging and (b) help them to report cases of over-staging.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","47509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596066","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>We have high passenger satisfaction and one of the safest railways for passengers of any major network in Europe. At the heart of this success lies a diverse range of commercial passenger and freight operators working in partnership with Government and industry suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>With passenger numbers having more than doubled since privatisation, we want to deliver further improvements including a more joined-up approach to running the trains and tracks, and to make things work better for the public.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:30:46.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596066/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596066/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the potential merits of reforming the rail franchising system by reinstating sole ownership and maintenance of infrastructure and trains.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","47518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596067","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department is exploring the provision of additional rolling stock to Southeastern, in order to lengthen services and increase capacity for passengers. This requires extensive commercial negotiations with Southeastern. We are continuing to work with Southeastern to develop the business case, and an announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-17T13:21:47.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596067/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596067/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-07","Southeastern: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that Southeastern has access to sufficient rolling stock to enable it to alleviate capacity pressures across its London metro network.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","47481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596068","Wales Office","false","2016-10-12","The Government is committed to working closely with the Welsh Government to ensure the implications of any reforms for devolved administration services or budgets are properly understood.","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-10-12T12:18:28.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596068/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596068/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-07","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Wales of the proposal to transfer responsibility for attendance allowance to local authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","47503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596069","Wales Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Wales Office is not an employer in its own right and payroll services are provided by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) on our behalf.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-10-14T11:09:50.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596069/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596069/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-07","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of staff on the payroll of his Department who work in Westminster are (a) British nationals and (b) nationals of another country.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596070","Wales Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Wales Office does not employ any cleaners. The Department uses Ministry of Justice facilities management contracts, including the provision of cleaning for its Westminster estate.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-10-14T11:08:46.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596070/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596070/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-07","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, approximately how many (a) British and (b) non-British nationals are employed cleaning the Westminster estate of his Department.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","47573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596071","Wales Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK Government does not hold the specific figures requested. The decision to proceed with the first new nuclear power station for a generation will provide a huge boost to the regional economy including South Wales. Construction at the Hinkley site will provide 26,000 jobs and apprenticeships, and 64% of the project’s costs will be spent in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Welsh companies are already taking advantage of the opportunities this project presents, for example, Express Reinforcements in South Wales was given preferred bidder status for a £100m contract to supply 200,000 tonnes of reinforcing steel for the project.</p><p> </p><p>I would encourage businesses in Wales to register with EDF in order to take advantage of upcoming supply chain opportunities.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","46773 ; 46774 ; 46775","2016-10-14T11:07:20.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596071/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596071/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-07","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate he has made of the net benefit to the Welsh economy of the steel to be used in the construction of the Hinkley C nuclear power plant.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","46766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596072","Wales Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Government has put in place a robust legal framework to ensure workers can be represented by unions if that is their clear, democratic choice. The Government cannot get involved in individual cases such as this one. However, the law states that for a trade union to have the right to negotiate collectively and for its workplace representatives to be eligible for time off to carry out union duties, the union must be recognised by the employer.</p><p> </p><p>Statutory recognition (achieved through the Central Arbitration Committee – CAC) requires that a majority of the workforce support union recognition for collective bargaining with the employer.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-10-14T11:04:16.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596072/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596072/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-07","Lidl: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that GMB is able to negotiate on behalf of 200 workers at the Lidl warehouse in Bridgend.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","46767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596073","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK Government will guarantee EU funding for structural and investment fund projects in Wales, including agri-environment schemes, signed before we leave the EU. It will be for the Welsh Government to make an assessment of which projects should be pursued in areas of its competence, and this guarantee will apply to any such projects. The agricultural sector in Wales will receive the same level of funding that it would have received under Pillar 1 of CAP until the end of the Multi-Annual Financial Framework in 2020.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these steps taken by the UK Government, individuals and organisations in receipt of EU funds now have a greater degree of certainty about funding over the coming years. The UK Government will work with the Welsh Government to consider future funding arrangements for once the UK has left the EU.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","46748 ; 46769 ; 46770 ; 46771","2016-10-17T10:54:46.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596073/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-07","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount of funding the Welsh Government will lose in subsidies as a result of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","46768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596074","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>The UK Government will guarantee EU funding for structural and investment fund projects in Wales, including agri-environment schemes, signed before we leave the EU. It will be for the Welsh Government to make an assessment of which projects should be pursued in areas of its competence, and this guarantee will apply to any such projects. The agricultural sector in Wales will receive the same level of funding that it would have received under Pillar 1 of CAP until the end of the Multi-Annual Financial Framework in 2020.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these steps taken by the UK Government, individuals and organisations in receipt of EU funds now have a greater degree of certainty about funding over the coming years. The UK Government will work with the Welsh Government to consider future funding arrangements for once the UK has left the EU.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","46748 ; 46768 ; 46770 ; 46771","2016-10-17T10:54:46.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596074/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/596074/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-07","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to match the level of funding for Wales that is provided by the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","46769"
